{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T12:37:07.022766", "agent_name": "AstroDeepResearchAgent", "method_name": "load_cached_research", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "Cached research loaded from: deep_research_claude/Acetyl-CoA-Run1.txt", "user_message": "Config: deep_research_claude", "raw_response": "# Prebiotic synthesis of acetyl-CoA: from minerals to metabolism\n\n**Acetyl-CoA \u2014 or more precisely its simpler thioester analogs like methyl thioacetate \u2014 can be synthesized under plausible prebiotic conditions through at least five demonstrated routes**, all converging on transition-metal-sulfide-catalyzed carbonylation chemistry that mirrors the most ancient carbon fixation pathway in biology. The central reaction, CO + CH\u2083SH \u2192 CH\u2083COSCH\u2083 on nickel-iron sulfide surfaces, was first demonstrated by Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user in 1997 at just 0.2\u20130.5% yield, but has since been pushed to **35\u201356% yield** at room temperature and neutral pH through geoelectrochemical approaches (Kitadai et al., 2021, *Communications Chemistry*). Meanwhile, the 2024 breakthrough prebiotic synthesis of pantetheine \u2014 CoA's functional subunit \u2014 by Fairchild, Islam, Singh, and Powner (*Science*, 2024) has dramatically narrowed the gap between simple thioesters and the full cofactor. These advances place acetyl thioester chemistry at the nexus of the origin-of-life problem, connecting geochemistry to the emergence of core metabolism.\n\n---\n\n## Five convergent routes to prebiotic acetyl thioesters\n\nMultiple independent research programs have proposed or demonstrated pathways to acetyl thioesters from simple molecules (CO\u2082, CO, H\u2082, H\u2082S, CH\u2083SH). Each route emerges from a distinct geochemical scenario, yet all converge on remarkably similar chemistry \u2014 the metal-catalyzed union of a one-carbon carbonyl unit with a thiol.\n\n**Route 1: Iron-sulfur world carbonylation (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user).** G\u00fcnter W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user proposed in 1988 (*Microbiological Reviews*) that life originated on iron sulfide mineral surfaces through autotrophic surface metabolism. The thermodynamic engine is the \"pyrite-pulled\" reaction: FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + H\u2082 (\u0394G\u00b0 = **\u221238 to \u221242 kJ/mol**), which provides reducing equivalents for CO\u2082 fixation. In this framework, CO\u2082 is reduced to CO on mineral surfaces, then CO undergoes carbonylation with methanethiol to form methyl thioacetate \u2014 a prebiotic analog of acetyl-CoA. The mechanism involves nickel-mediated organometallic intermediates (Ni-CO, Ni-CH\u2083, Ni-acetyl) that parallel both the biological acetyl-CoA synthase reaction and the industrial Monsanto acetic acid process.\n\n**Route 2: Alkaline hydrothermal vent synthesis (Russell and Martin).** Michael Russell proposed in 1994 (*Journal of Molecular Evolution*) that life emerged at submarine alkaline hydrothermal vents, where serpentinization-derived H\u2082-rich, alkaline fluids (pH 9\u201311) encountered the CO\u2082-rich, mildly acidic Hadean ocean (pH ~5\u20136). Iron-nickel sulfide precipitates lining vent micropores catalyze a geochemical analog of the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway: CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 CO on one branch, CO\u2082 \u2192 CH\u2083-group on another, with convergence at NiFe-sulfide surfaces to form acetyl thioesters. Natural **pH gradients of ~3\u20135 units** across inorganic membranes provide an electrochemical driving force of ~250\u2013300 mV, sufficient to power CO\u2082 reduction. Martin and Russell (2007, *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B*) detailed how acetyl phosphate (\u0394G'\u2070 of hydrolysis = **\u221243 kJ/mol**, exceeding ATP's \u221231 kJ/mol) would serve as the primordial energy currency.\n\n**Route 3: Native metal CO\u2082 reduction (Moran, Varma, Muchowska).** Varma, Muchowska, Chatelain, and Moran (2018, *Nature Ecology & Evolution*) showed that native iron (Fe\u2070) directly reduces CO\u2082 to acetate (**up to 280 \u00b5M**), pyruvate, and formate at 30\u2013100\u00b0C under 1\u201340 bar CO\u2082. This bypasses the kinetic barriers that stymied earlier attempts at H\u2082-driven CO\u2082 reduction. The midpoint potential of Fe\u2070 oxidation is sufficient to reduce CO\u2082 without the flavin-based electron bifurcation that biological systems require. Preiner et al. (2020, *Nature Ecology & Evolution*) extended this using hydrothermal minerals \u2014 **greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084), and awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe)** \u2014 to produce formate (up to **200 mM**), acetate (~100 \u00b5M), and pyruvate (~10 \u00b5M) from H\u2082 + CO\u2082 at 100\u00b0C. Beyazay et al. (2023, *Nature Communications*) achieved the same product spectrum at just **25\u00b0C** under 25 bar with Ni\u2083Fe nanoparticles, and demonstrated further conversion of pyruvate to citramalate.\n\n**Route 4: Cyanosulfidic protometabolism (Sutherland).** John Sutherland's group at MRC Cambridge developed a systems chemistry approach where HCN and H\u2082S, driven by UV photoredox cycling with Cu(I)/Cu(II) catalysis, generate precursors to nucleotides, amino acids, and lipids from common feedstocks (Patel et al., 2015, *Nature Chemistry*). While this framework does not directly produce acetyl thioesters, it generates **pyruvate in ~14% yield** through UV-driven oxidation of \u03b1-hydroxy acids (Ritson, 2021, *Science Advances*) \u2014 a key branch-point intermediate for thioester formation via oxidative decarboxylation. Critically, Leqraa et al. (2020, *Scientific Reports*) demonstrated that pyruvate reacts with disulfides under UV irradiation to yield thioacetate esters without requiring an external oxidant, bridging cyanosulfidic chemistry to thioester metabolism.\n\n**Route 5: High-pressure organometallic synthesis (Cody).** Cody et al. (2000, *Science*) demonstrated that at 250\u00b0C and 50\u2013200 MPa \u2014 conditions simulating deep hydrothermal systems \u2014 CO reacts with iron sulfide and alkyl thiols to form organometallic iron-sulfur-carbonyl phases that produce pyruvic acid. This pressure-enhanced pathway operates through organometallic intermediates structurally analogous to CODH/ACS active sites.\n\n---\n\n## Key intermediates and branch points\n\nThe path from CO\u2082 to acetyl thioesters passes through a small number of critical intermediates, several of which serve as branch points connecting multiple biosynthetic pathways.\n\n**Carbon monoxide** is the pivotal C\u2081 intermediate in virtually all routes. It is generated from CO\u2082 by electroreduction on iron sulfide minerals, by the reverse water-gas shift reaction (CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO + H\u2082O) on Fe/Ni surfaces, or by UV photolysis. CO binds to nickel centers on mineral surfaces \u2014 the same chemistry exploited by the CODH enzyme's C-cluster \u2014 and undergoes migratory insertion with methyl groups to form the C\u2013C bond of the acetyl unit. **Formate (HCOO\u207b)** is the first stable reduction product of CO\u2082, produced in extraordinary abundance \u2014 up to **200 mM** on awaruite (Preiner et al., 2020). Formate is the entry point of the methyl branch of the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway and can be further reduced to formaldehyde, methanol, and methyl groups.\n\n**Methanethiol (CH\u2083SH)** is the essential thiol substrate. It is present in modern hydrothermal fluids at micromolar to low-millimolar concentrations and can be generated abiotically from CO\u2082 reduction in sulfide-rich environments. Methanethiol provides both the thiol leaving group and, in some formulations, the methyl group for the carbonylation reaction. **Pyruvate** occupies a unique position as the most connected branch-point metabolite \u2014 it is the precursor to all amino acids (via transamination), to acetyl-CoA (via oxidative decarboxylation), and to oxaloacetate (via carboxylation). Goldford et al. (2017, *Cell*) computationally identified pyruvate and glyoxylate as the most well-connected C-H-O compounds in a hypothetical phosphate-free proto-metabolism. Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (2019, *Nature*) demonstrated that Fe\u00b2\u207a promotes a reaction network starting from pyruvate and glyoxylate that builds **9 of 11 Krebs cycle intermediates**.\n\n**S-Methyl thioacetate (CH\u2083COSCH\u2083)** is the simplest activated thioester analog of acetyl-CoA. Its hydrolysis releases **\u221231 kJ/mol** of free energy \u2014 comparable to ATP hydrolysis \u2014 making it a plausible primordial energy currency as proposed by de Duve's \"thioester world\" hypothesis (1991). **Acetyl phosphate** bridges thioester and phosphate metabolism: formed non-enzymatically from acetyl thioesters and inorganic phosphate, it has an even higher phosphorylating potential (\u0394G'\u2070 = \u221243 kJ/mol) than ATP.\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts mirror enzyme active sites with striking fidelity\n\nThe most compelling evidence connecting prebiotic geochemistry to biochemistry is the structural and functional correspondence between hydrothermal mineral catalysts and the metalloenzyme active sites that catalyze acetyl-CoA synthesis in modern organisms.\n\n**Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**, the sulfide analog of magnetite, contains cubic **[Fe\u2084S\u2084] structural units** that are geometrically identical to the [4Fe-4S] thiocubane clusters found in ferredoxins and in the CODH/ACS enzyme complex. Fe\u2013S bond distances in greigite match those in ferredoxin active sites within **0.01\u20130.13 \u00c5** (Roldan et al., 2015, *Chemical Communications*). Greigite was confirmed to be thermodynamically stable \u2014 not metastable as previously assumed \u2014 with low surface energy supporting nanoparticle catalytic activity (Navarro-Gonz\u00e1lez et al., 2020, *PNAS*). Electrochemically, greigite reduces CO\u2082 under ambient conditions to formic acid, methanol, acetic acid, and pyruvic acid (Roldan et al., 2015). **Nickel-bearing greigite** structurally resembles the C-cluster ([NiFe\u2083S\u2084]) of carbon monoxide dehydrogenase (CODH), which catalyzes the reversible reduction CO\u2082 \u21cc CO with virtually no overpotential. Doping FeS with Ni to form violarite (FeNi\u2082S\u2084) enhances CO\u2082 electroreduction selectivity **~85-fold** compared to pure FeS.\n\n**Mackinawite (FeS)**, the initial precipitate from Fe\u00b2\u207a + S\u00b2\u207b in hydrothermal systems, has a layered tetragonal structure comprising [2Fe-2S] rhombic units \u2014 the same motif as [2Fe-2S] ferredoxin clusters. It forms spontaneous inorganic membranes at alkaline hydrothermal vents. When partially electroreduced to metallic Fe\u2070 (designated FeS_PERM), mackinawite shows exceptional catalytic capability for multiple reactions in the reverse tricarboxylic acid cycle (Kitadai et al., 2019). Nan et al. (2024, *Nature Communications*) showed mackinawite catalyzes H\u2082-driven CO\u2082 reduction to methanol at 80\u2013120\u00b0C, with **Mn-doped FeS increasing methanol production five-fold**.\n\n**Awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe)**, a native nickel-iron alloy formed during serpentinization, proved the most efficient catalyst for multi-carbon product formation from H\u2082 + CO\u2082 in Preiner et al.'s 2020 experiments. Its catalytic role parallels the Ni\u2070 site in the ACS A-cluster, where nickel cycles between oxidation states to mediate methyl migration and CO insertion. **Green rust/fougerite**, a mixed-valence Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b3\u207a layered double hydroxide, has been proposed by Russell (2023, *Frontiers in Microbiology*) as a membrane-spanning catalytic engine at alkaline vents. Its ~150 hydrous interlayers can concentrate anions up to **10\u2076-fold**, potentially solving the concentration problem, while its redox versatility (stable across Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe_total ratios of 1/3 to 2/3) enables electron bifurcation analogous to biological systems.\n\nThe biological acetyl-CoA synthase (ACS) A-cluster contains a unique [Ni_p\u2013Ni_d\u2013Fe\u2084S\u2084] center where the proximal nickel (Ni_p) cycles between Ni\u2070/Ni\u00b9\u207a/Ni\u00b2\u207a states during catalysis \u2014 binding CO, accepting a methyl group, forming an acetyl intermediate, and transferring it to CoA-SH via reductive thiolysis. Manesis et al. (2022, *PNAS*) created an artificial nickel metalloenzyme within the azurin protein scaffold that reproduces this chemistry at **up to 70% yield**, demonstrating that the catalytic principle requires only a single nickel center in a minimal protein environment. Wilson et al. (2024, *JACS*) synthesized heterometallic [NiFe\u2084S\u2084] clusters by inserting Ni\u2070 into oxidized [Fe\u2084S\u2084]\u00b3\u207a, establishing the first experimental precedent for the Ni\u00b9\u207a oxidation state in iron-sulfur cluster chemistry \u2014 a critical mechanistic link between mineral and enzymatic catalysis. Jordan et al. (2021, *Nature Communications*) demonstrated that [4Fe-4S] and [2Fe-2S] clusters **self-assemble spontaneously** from Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b3\u207a, S\u00b2\u207b, and micromolar cysteine at alkaline pH, with bicarbonate stabilizing the clusters. These clusters exhibit midpoint redox potentials of approximately **\u2212500 mV vs SHE**, appropriate for CO\u2082 reduction.\n\n---\n\n## Landmark experiments and quantitative benchmarks\n\nThe experimental evidence for prebiotic thioester synthesis has progressed dramatically from early proof-of-concept demonstrations to increasingly realistic and efficient systems.\n\n**Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997, *Science* 276: 245\u2013247)** provided the foundational demonstration: coprecipitated NiS/FeS in sealed anaerobic vials at 100\u00b0C under 1.05 bar CO, with 100 \u00b5mol CH\u2083SH in 10 mL aqueous solution at initial pH ~8, produced **41 \u00b5mol acetic acid** and detectable methyl thioacetate after 7 days. With NiS alone (no FeS), 7\u20139 \u00b5mol of methyl thioacetate formed in 20 hours. Adding catalytic selenium enabled one-pot synthesis from CO and H\u2082S alone, without externally added methanethiol. However, the CO concentration (~350 mM in solution) was **~500\u00d7 higher** and CH\u2083SH (~3,700\u00d7) higher than concentrations measured in natural hydrothermal fluids (Camprub\u00ed et al., 2017, *IUBMB Life*), limiting geochemical plausibility.\n\n**Kitadai et al. (2021, *Communications Chemistry* 4: 37)** achieved a transformative advance: under simulated geoelectrochemical conditions (\u22120.6 to \u22121.0 V vs SHE), NiS gradually reduced to Ni\u2083S\u2082 and then Ni\u2070, accumulating surface-bound CO from CO\u2082 electroreduction. This partially reduced NiS (NiS_PERM) catalyzed methyl thioacetate formation at **room temperature, neutral pH, with up to 35% yield** based on CO. Coprecipitation with CoS pushed yields to **56%**. This represents a **~175-fold improvement** over Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's original yield, under far milder conditions. The geoelectrochemical driving force \u2014 redox gradients across hydrothermal chimney walls \u2014 is geologically realistic.\n\n**Preiner et al. (2020, *Nature Ecology & Evolution* 4: 534\u2013542)** demonstrated that three naturally occurring hydrothermal minerals catalyze a geochemical analog of the complete Wood-Ljungdahl pathway: greigite, magnetite, and awaruite convert H\u2082 + CO\u2082 at 100\u00b0C in alkaline solution to formate (**up to 200 mM**), acetate (~100 \u00b5M), pyruvate (~10 \u00b5M), methanol (~100 \u00b5M), and methane. The product spectrum precisely mirrors the biological pathway's intermediates and products.\n\n**Cody et al. (2000, *Science* 289: 1337\u20131340)** demonstrated pyruvate synthesis at 250\u00b0C and 50\u2013200 MPa from CO + FeS + alkyl thiols, showing that high-pressure hydrothermal conditions favor organometallic iron-sulfur-carbonyl intermediates. **Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (2019, *Nature* 569: 104\u2013107)** showed Fe\u00b2\u207a promotes construction of 9 of 11 Krebs cycle intermediates from pyruvate and glyoxylate, with addition of hydroxylamine and Fe\u2070 yielding four biological amino acids \u2014 demonstrating that prebiotic thioester-related chemistry connects seamlessly to amino acid biosynthesis.\n\nRecent work has expanded both the reaction scope and environmental settings. **El Qami et al. (2025, *Scientific Reports*)** showed 1,4-diacids form cyclic anhydrides upon drying over silica, which react with thiols to produce succinyl and citryl thioester analogs \u2014 a self-activating mechanism requiring no ATP equivalent. **Frenkel-Pinter et al. (2022, *Nature Communications*)** demonstrated that simply drying mercaptoacids with amino acids produces thiodepsipeptides containing both peptide and thioester bonds across a wide range of pH and temperature. **Cho et al. (2025, *Nature Chemistry*)** showed that cysteine reacting spontaneously with short-chain thioesters produces protocell-like structures, while **Kent et al. (2025, *ACS Central Science*)** demonstrated that tRNAs acylated with thioesters support efficient protein biosynthesis by wild-type ribosomes \u2014 evidence that thioester intermediates may have preceded oxoester intermediates in early translation.\n\n---\n\n## Environments that favor each step of the pathway\n\nDifferent geochemical settings optimize different steps of the pathway from CO\u2082 to acetyl thioesters, suggesting either a single environment with diverse microenvironments or a multi-setting scenario.\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents** (Lost City-type: 40\u2013120\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311, H\u2082 up to 14 mM, continuous for >100,000 years) are optimal for the initial CO\u2082 reduction steps. Serpentinization generates both the reductant (H\u2082) and the catalyst (awaruite, magnetite, greigite) simultaneously. The pH gradient across FeS/NiS membranes (~5 units on Hadean Earth) provides an electrochemical driving force of 250\u2013300 mV \u2014 sufficient to power CO\u2082 reduction to CO and formate. Microporous inorganic compartments within chimney structures solve the concentration problem while providing proto-cellular confinement (Russell and Hall, 1997). However, thioester stability is severely limited under these conditions: **methyl thioacetate half-life at pH 10, 100\u00b0C is only ~43 seconds** (Mayer et al., 2024, *iScience*), compared to **155 days at pH 7, 23\u00b0C** (Brosnan et al., 2011, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*). This stability constraint strongly favors thioester accumulation in **cooler, more acidic microenvironments** \u2014 perhaps at the ocean-facing exterior of vent structures where mixing with acidic seawater moderates both temperature and pH.\n\n**Surface evaporitic pools** and terrestrial hot springs favor condensation and polymerization steps. Wet-dry cycling drives anhydride and thioester bond formation during drying phases. UV irradiation provides photochemical energy for radical reactions, including pyruvate oxidative decarboxylation to acetyl thioesters (Leqraa et al., 2020). Nan et al. (2024, *Nature Communications*) demonstrated FeS-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to methanol at 80\u2013120\u00b0C in conditions mimicking terrestrial hot springs, with UV-visible light enhancing activity. **Thermophoresis** in rock pore networks can selectively accumulate diverse prebiotic building blocks through temperature gradients (Matreux et al., 2024).\n\n---\n\n## Unresolved challenges and the path forward\n\nDespite remarkable experimental progress, several fundamental problems remain.\n\n**The CoA complexity gap** is perhaps the most significant. Acetyl-CoA is a large, information-rich molecule containing pantothenic acid, \u03b2-alanine, cysteamine, and 3'-phospho-ADP \u2014 each component presenting its own prebiotic synthesis challenge. However, three developments have substantially narrowed this gap. First, **Fairchild et al. (2024, *Science* 383: 911\u2013918)** achieved the first prebiotically plausible synthesis of pantetheine \u2014 CoA's catalytically active subunit \u2014 through chemoselective nitrile chemistry in water at room temperature, dramatically outperforming Miller's earlier attempt (Keefe, Newton, and Miller, 1995, *Nature*). Second, Goldford et al. (2017, *Cell*) computationally demonstrated that substituting pantetheine for CoA maintains network viability in a phosphate-free proto-metabolism. Third, even simpler thiols \u2014 methanethiol, cysteamine, coenzyme M (HSCH\u2082CH\u2082SO\u2083\u207b) \u2014 can serve the same chemical function, as demonstrated by near-quantitative aminoacyl-thiol yields using coenzyme M (Singh et al., 2025, *Nature*).\n\n**The concentration problem** persists for dilute products in open aqueous environments. Proposed solutions include microporous vent confinement, thermophoretic accumulation in rock fissures, wet-dry cycling in surface pools, eutectic concentration in ice, and the remarkable **10\u2076-fold concentration** achievable in green rust interlayers. Thiol-thioester exchange (k = 1.7 M\u207b\u00b9s\u207b\u00b9 at pH 7, 23\u00b0C) is several orders of magnitude faster than thioester hydrolysis, meaning that even dilute thioester pools can efficiently transfer their acetyl groups to new thiol acceptors before being lost to hydrolysis.\n\n**Selectivity and the \"chemical mess\" problem** \u2014 the tendency of prebiotic reactions to produce complex mixtures of products rather than the specific molecules biology uses \u2014 remains a core challenge. Mineral surfaces provide some selectivity through preferential adsorption and oriented catalysis, but lack the precise substrate positioning of enzyme active sites. The emerging \"systems chemistry\" approach (Sutherland, Powner) addresses this by identifying reaction networks where selectivity emerges from the interplay of multiple concurrent reactions rather than from any single selective step.\n\n**The mineral-to-enzyme transition** \u2014 how catalysis migrated from mineral surfaces to soluble iron-sulfur clusters to metalloproteins \u2014 is incompletely understood. Jordan et al.'s demonstration of spontaneous [4Fe-4S] cluster self-assembly from simple precursors and Wilson et al.'s synthesis of heterometallic [NiFe\u2084S\u2084] clusters provide critical missing pieces, but the full trajectory from greigite surfaces to CODH/ACS holoenzyme remains speculative. Notably, the redox bifunctionality of nickel (cycling between Ni\u2070/Ni\u00b9\u207a/Ni\u00b2\u207a/Ni\u00b3\u207a) that is essential for ACS catalysis has not been observed in natural nickel-bearing minerals \u2014 only under imposed electrochemical conditions \u2014 raising questions about whether mineral catalysis alone could have supported the full carbonylation mechanism.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of acetyl thioesters has progressed from theoretical proposals to experimentally demonstrated chemistry achieving yields comparable to enzymatic reactions. The field has converged on a core insight: **the same nickel-iron-sulfide chemistry that catalyzes acetyl-CoA synthesis in the most ancient biological pathway also operates on mineral surfaces under geologically realistic conditions**. The structural identity between greigite [Fe\u2084S\u2084] units and ferredoxin clusters, and between Ni-doped iron sulfides and CODH/ACS active sites, is not merely analogical but reflects a direct evolutionary continuity from geochemistry to biochemistry. The most productive current direction combines the Strasbourg group's native-metal CO\u2082 reduction chemistry with the Kitadai group's geoelectrochemical thioester synthesis and the Powner group's prebiotic CoA-precursor synthesis \u2014 together these define a plausible, experimentally grounded pathway from volcanic gases to the central energy-coupling molecule of all life. The critical next milestone is demonstrating a complete, continuous sequence from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 to an acetyl thioester in a single geochemically realistic reactor \u2014 a goal that, given the pace of recent advances, appears increasingly within reach.", "parsed_response": {"source": "deep_research_claude/Acetyl-CoA-Run1.txt", "config": "deep_research_claude", "length": 22405}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 0.0, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T12:37:07.024569", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Acetyl-CoA\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Acetyl-CoA. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of acetyl-CoA: from minerals to metabolism\n\n**Acetyl-CoA \u2014 or more precisely its simpler thioester analogs like methyl thioacetate \u2014 can be synthesized under plausible prebiotic conditions through at least five demonstrated routes**, all converging on transition-metal-sulfide-catalyzed carbonylation chemistry that mirrors the most ancient carbon fixation pathway in biology. The central reaction, CO + CH\u2083SH \u2192 CH\u2083COSCH\u2083 on nickel-iron sulfide surfaces, was first demonstrated by Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user in 1997 at just 0.2\u20130.5% yield, but has since been pushed to **35\u201356% yield** at room temperature and neutral pH through geoelectrochemical approaches (Kitadai et al., 2021, *Communications Chemistry*). Meanwhile, the 2024 breakthrough prebiotic synthesis of pantetheine \u2014 CoA's functional subunit \u2014 by Fairchild, Islam, Singh, and Powner (*Science*, 2024) has dramatically narrowed the gap between simple thioesters and the full cofactor. These advances place acetyl thioester chemistry at the nexus of the origin-of-life problem, connecting geochemistry to the emergence of core metabolism.\n\n---\n\n## Five convergent routes to prebiotic acetyl thioesters\n\nMultiple independent research programs have proposed or demonstrated pathways to acetyl thioesters from simple molecules (CO\u2082, CO, H\u2082, H\u2082S, CH\u2083SH). Each route emerges from a distinct geochemical scenario, yet all converge on remarkably similar chemistry \u2014 the metal-catalyzed union of a one-carbon carbonyl unit with a thiol.\n\n**Route 1: Iron-sulfur world carbonylation (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user).** G\u00fcnter W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user proposed in 1988 (*Microbiological Reviews*) that life originated on iron sulfide mineral surfaces through autotrophic surface metabolism. The thermodynamic engine is the \"pyrite-pulled\" reaction: FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + H\u2082 (\u0394G\u00b0 = **\u221238 to \u221242 kJ/mol**), which provides reducing equivalents for CO\u2082 fixation. In this framework, CO\u2082 is reduced to CO on mineral surfaces, then CO undergoes carbonylation with methanethiol to form methyl thioacetate \u2014 a prebiotic analog of acetyl-CoA. The mechanism involves nickel-mediated organometallic intermediates (Ni-CO, Ni-CH\u2083, Ni-acetyl) that parallel both the biological acetyl-CoA synthase reaction and the industrial Monsanto acetic acid process.\n\n**Route 2: Alkaline hydrothermal vent synthesis (Russell and Martin).** Michael Russell proposed in 1994 (*Journal of Molecular Evolution*) that life emerged at submarine alkaline hydrothermal vents, where serpentinization-derived H\u2082-rich, alkaline fluids (pH 9\u201311) encountered the CO\u2082-rich, mildly acidic Hadean ocean (pH ~5\u20136). Iron-nickel sulfide precipitates lining vent micropores catalyze a geochemical analog of the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway: CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 CO on one branch, CO\u2082 \u2192 CH\u2083-group on another, with convergence at NiFe-sulfide surfaces to form acetyl thioesters. Natural **pH gradients of ~3\u20135 units** across inorganic membranes provide an electrochemical driving force of ~250\u2013300 mV, sufficient to power CO\u2082 reduction. Martin and Russell (2007, *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B*) detailed how acetyl phosphate (\u0394G'\u2070 of hydrolysis = **\u221243 kJ/mol**, exceeding ATP's \u221231 kJ/mol) would serve as the primordial energy currency.\n\n**Route 3: Native metal CO\u2082 reduction (Moran, Varma, Muchowska).** Varma, Muchowska, Chatelain, and Moran (2018, *Nature Ecology & Evolution*) showed that native iron (Fe\u2070) directly reduces CO\u2082 to acetate (**up to 280 \u00b5M**), pyruvate, and formate at 30\u2013100\u00b0C under 1\u201340 bar CO\u2082. This bypasses the kinetic barriers that stymied earlier attempts at H\u2082-driven CO\u2082 reduction. The midpoint potential of Fe\u2070 oxidation is sufficient to reduce CO\u2082 without the flavin-based electron bifurcation that biological systems require. Preiner et al. (2020, *Nature Ecology & Evolution*) extended this using hydrothermal minerals \u2014 **greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084), and awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe)** \u2014 to produce formate (up to **200 mM**), acetate (~100 \u00b5M), and pyruvate (~10 \u00b5M) from H\u2082 + CO\u2082 at 100\u00b0C. Beyazay et al. (2023, *Nature Communications*) achieved the same product spectrum at just **25\u00b0C** under 25 bar with Ni\u2083Fe nanoparticles, and demonstrated further conversion of pyruvate to citramalate.\n\n**Route 4: Cyanosulfidic protometabolism (Sutherland).** John Sutherland's group at MRC Cambridge developed a systems chemistry approach where HCN and H\u2082S, driven by UV photoredox cycling with Cu(I)/Cu(II) catalysis, generate precursors to nucleotides, amino acids, and lipids from common feedstocks (Patel et al., 2015, *Nature Chemistry*). While this framework does not directly produce acetyl thioesters, it generates **pyruvate in ~14% yield** through UV-driven oxidation of \u03b1-hydroxy acids (Ritson, 2021, *Science Advances*) \u2014 a key branch-point intermediate for thioester formation via oxidative decarboxylation. Critically, Leqraa et al. (2020, *Scientific Reports*) demonstrated that pyruvate reacts with disulfides under UV irradiation to yield thioacetate esters without requiring an external oxidant, bridging cyanosulfidic chemistry to thioester metabolism.\n\n**Route 5: High-pressure organometallic synthesis (Cody).** Cody et al. (2000, *Science*) demonstrated that at 250\u00b0C and 50\u2013200 MPa \u2014 conditions simulating deep hydrothermal systems \u2014 CO reacts with iron sulfide and alkyl thiols to form organometallic iron-sulfur-carbonyl phases that produce pyruvic acid. This pressure-enhanced pathway operates through organometallic intermediates structurally analogous to CODH/ACS active sites.\n\n---\n\n## Key intermediates and branch points\n\nThe path from CO\u2082 to acetyl thioesters passes through a small number of critical intermediates, several of which serve as branch points connecting multiple biosynthetic pathways.\n\n**Carbon monoxide** is the pivotal C\u2081 intermediate in virtually all routes. It is generated from CO\u2082 by electroreduction on iron sulfide minerals, by the reverse water-gas shift reaction (CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO + H\u2082O) on Fe/Ni surfaces, or by UV photolysis. CO binds to nickel centers on mineral surfaces \u2014 the same chemistry exploited by the CODH enzyme's C-cluster \u2014 and undergoes migratory insertion with methyl groups to form the C\u2013C bond of the acetyl unit. **Formate (HCOO\u207b)** is the first stable reduction product of CO\u2082, produced in extraordinary abundance \u2014 up to **200 mM** on awaruite (Preiner et al., 2020). Formate is the entry point of the methyl branch of the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway and can be further reduced to formaldehyde, methanol, and methyl groups.\n\n**Methanethiol (CH\u2083SH)** is the essential thiol substrate. It is present in modern hydrothermal fluids at micromolar to low-millimolar concentrations and can be generated abiotically from CO\u2082 reduction in sulfide-rich environments. Methanethiol provides both the thiol leaving group and, in some formulations, the methyl group for the carbonylation reaction. **Pyruvate** occupies a unique position as the most connected branch-point metabolite \u2014 it is the precursor to all amino acids (via transamination), to acetyl-CoA (via oxidative decarboxylation), and to oxaloacetate (via carboxylation). Goldford et al. (2017, *Cell*) computationally identified pyruvate and glyoxylate as the most well-connected C-H-O compounds in a hypothetical phosphate-free proto-metabolism. Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (2019, *Nature*) demonstrated that Fe\u00b2\u207a promotes a reaction network starting from pyruvate and glyoxylate that builds **9 of 11 Krebs cycle intermediates**.\n\n**S-Methyl thioacetate (CH\u2083COSCH\u2083)** is the simplest activated thioester analog of acetyl-CoA. Its hydrolysis releases **\u221231 kJ/mol** of free energy \u2014 comparable to ATP hydrolysis \u2014 making it a plausible primordial energy currency as proposed by de Duve's \"thioester world\" hypothesis (1991). **Acetyl phosphate** bridges thioester and phosphate metabolism: formed non-enzymatically from acetyl thioesters and inorganic phosphate, it has an even higher phosphorylating potential (\u0394G'\u2070 = \u221243 kJ/mol) than ATP.\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts mirror enzyme active sites with striking fidelity\n\nThe most compelling evidence connecting prebiotic geochemistry to biochemistry is the structural and functional correspondence between hydrothermal mineral catalysts and the metalloenzyme active sites that catalyze acetyl-CoA synthesis in modern organisms.\n\n**Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**, the sulfide analog of magnetite, contains cubic **[Fe\u2084S\u2084] structural units** that are geometrically identical to the [4Fe-4S] thiocubane clusters found in ferredoxins and in the CODH/ACS enzyme complex. Fe\u2013S bond distances in greigite match those in ferredoxin active sites within **0.01\u20130.13 \u00c5** (Roldan et al., 2015, *Chemical Communications*). Greigite was confirmed to be thermodynamically stable \u2014 not metastable as previously assumed \u2014 with low surface energy supporting nanoparticle catalytic activity (Navarro-Gonz\u00e1lez et al., 2020, *PNAS*). Electrochemically, greigite reduces CO\u2082 under ambient conditions to formic acid, methanol, acetic acid, and pyruvic acid (Roldan et al., 2015). **Nickel-bearing greigite** structurally resembles the C-cluster ([NiFe\u2083S\u2084]) of carbon monoxide dehydrogenase (CODH), which catalyzes the reversible reduction CO\u2082 \u21cc CO with virtually no overpotential. Doping FeS with Ni to form violarite (FeNi\u2082S\u2084) enhances CO\u2082 electroreduction selectivity **~85-fold** compared to pure FeS.\n\n**Mackinawite (FeS)**, the initial precipitate from Fe\u00b2\u207a + S\u00b2\u207b in hydrothermal systems, has a layered tetragonal structure comprising [2Fe-2S] rhombic units \u2014 the same motif as [2Fe-2S] ferredoxin clusters. It forms spontaneous inorganic membranes at alkaline hydrothermal vents. When partially electroreduced to metallic Fe\u2070 (designated FeS_PERM), mackinawite shows exceptional catalytic capability for multiple reactions in the reverse tricarboxylic acid cycle (Kitadai et al., 2019). Nan et al. (2024, *Nature Communications*) showed mackinawite catalyzes H\u2082-driven CO\u2082 reduction to methanol at 80\u2013120\u00b0C, with **Mn-doped FeS increasing methanol production five-fold**.\n\n**Awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe)**, a native nickel-iron alloy formed during serpentinization, proved the most efficient catalyst for multi-carbon product formation from H\u2082 + CO\u2082 in Preiner et al.'s 2020 experiments. Its catalytic role parallels the Ni\u2070 site in the ACS A-cluster, where nickel cycles between oxidation states to mediate methyl migration and CO insertion. **Green rust/fougerite**, a mixed-valence Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b3\u207a layered double hydroxide, has been proposed by Russell (2023, *Frontiers in Microbiology*) as a membrane-spanning catalytic engine at alkaline vents. Its ~150 hydrous interlayers can concentrate anions up to **10\u2076-fold**, potentially solving the concentration problem, while its redox versatility (stable across Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe_total ratios of 1/3 to 2/3) enables electron bifurcation analogous to biological systems.\n\nThe biological acetyl-CoA synthase (ACS) A-cluster contains a unique [Ni_p\u2013Ni_d\u2013Fe\u2084S\u2084] center where the proximal nickel (Ni_p) cycles between Ni\u2070/Ni\u00b9\u207a/Ni\u00b2\u207a states during catalysis \u2014 binding CO, accepting a methyl group, forming an acetyl intermediate, and transferring it to CoA-SH via reductive thiolysis. Manesis et al. (2022, *PNAS*) created an artificial nickel metalloenzyme within the azurin protein scaffold that reproduces this chemistry at **up to 70% yield**, demonstrating that the catalytic principle requires only a single nickel center in a minimal protein environment. Wilson et al. (2024, *JACS*) synthesized heterometallic [NiFe\u2084S\u2084] clusters by inserting Ni\u2070 into oxidized [Fe\u2084S\u2084]\u00b3\u207a, establishing the first experimental precedent for the Ni\u00b9\u207a oxidation state in iron-sulfur cluster chemistry \u2014 a critical mechanistic link between mineral and enzymatic catalysis. Jordan et al. (2021, *Nature Communications*) demonstrated that [4Fe-4S] and [2Fe-2S] clusters **self-assemble spontaneously** from Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b3\u207a, S\u00b2\u207b, and micromolar cysteine at alkaline pH, with bicarbonate stabilizing the clusters. These clusters exhibit midpoint redox potentials of approximately **\u2212500 mV vs SHE**, appropriate for CO\u2082 reduction.\n\n---\n\n## Landmark experiments and quantitative benchmarks\n\nThe experimental evidence for prebiotic thioester synthesis has progressed dramatically from early proof-of-concept demonstrations to increasingly realistic and efficient systems.\n\n**Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997, *Science* 276: 245\u2013247)** provided the foundational demonstration: coprecipitated NiS/FeS in sealed anaerobic vials at 100\u00b0C under 1.05 bar CO, with 100 \u00b5mol CH\u2083SH in 10 mL aqueous solution at initial pH ~8, produced **41 \u00b5mol acetic acid** and detectable methyl thioacetate after 7 days. With NiS alone (no FeS), 7\u20139 \u00b5mol of methyl thioacetate formed in 20 hours. Adding catalytic selenium enabled one-pot synthesis from CO and H\u2082S alone, without externally added methanethiol. However, the CO concentration (~350 mM in solution) was **~500\u00d7 higher** and CH\u2083SH (~3,700\u00d7) higher than concentrations measured in natural hydrothermal fluids (Camprub\u00ed et al., 2017, *IUBMB Life*), limiting geochemical plausibility.\n\n**Kitadai et al. (2021, *Communications Chemistry* 4: 37)** achieved a transformative advance: under simulated geoelectrochemical conditions (\u22120.6 to \u22121.0 V vs SHE), NiS gradually reduced to Ni\u2083S\u2082 and then Ni\u2070, accumulating surface-bound CO from CO\u2082 electroreduction. This partially reduced NiS (NiS_PERM) catalyzed methyl thioacetate formation at **room temperature, neutral pH, with up to 35% yield** based on CO. Coprecipitation with CoS pushed yields to **56%**. This represents a **~175-fold improvement** over Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's original yield, under far milder conditions. The geoelectrochemical driving force \u2014 redox gradients across hydrothermal chimney walls \u2014 is geologically realistic.\n\n**Preiner et al. (2020, *Nature Ecology & Evolution* 4: 534\u2013542)** demonstrated that three naturally occurring hydrothermal minerals catalyze a geochemical analog of the complete Wood-Ljungdahl pathway: greigite, magnetite, and awaruite convert H\u2082 + CO\u2082 at 100\u00b0C in alkaline solution to formate (**up to 200 mM**), acetate (~100 \u00b5M), pyruvate (~10 \u00b5M), methanol (~100 \u00b5M), and methane. The product spectrum precisely mirrors the biological pathway's intermediates and products.\n\n**Cody et al. (2000, *Science* 289: 1337\u20131340)** demonstrated pyruvate synthesis at 250\u00b0C and 50\u2013200 MPa from CO + FeS + alkyl thiols, showing that high-pressure hydrothermal conditions favor organometallic iron-sulfur-carbonyl intermediates. **Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (2019, *Nature* 569: 104\u2013107)** showed Fe\u00b2\u207a promotes construction of 9 of 11 Krebs cycle intermediates from pyruvate and glyoxylate, with addition of hydroxylamine and Fe\u2070 yielding four biological amino acids \u2014 demonstrating that prebiotic thioester-related chemistry connects seamlessly to amino acid biosynthesis.\n\nRecent work has expanded both the reaction scope and environmental settings. **El Qami et al. (2025, *Scientific Reports*)** showed 1,4-diacids form cyclic anhydrides upon drying over silica, which react with thiols to produce succinyl and citryl thioester analogs \u2014 a self-activating mechanism requiring no ATP equivalent. **Frenkel-Pinter et al. (2022, *Nature Communications*)** demonstrated that simply drying mercaptoacids with amino acids produces thiodepsipeptides containing both peptide and thioester bonds across a wide range of pH and temperature. **Cho et al. (2025, *Nature Chemistry*)** showed that cysteine reacting spontaneously with short-chain thioesters produces protocell-like structures, while **Kent et al. (2025, *ACS Central Science*)** demonstrated that tRNAs acylated with thioesters support efficient protein biosynthesis by wild-type ribosomes \u2014 evidence that thioester intermediates may have preceded oxoester intermediates in early translation.\n\n---\n\n## Environments that favor each step of the pathway\n\nDifferent geochemical settings optimize different steps of the pathway from CO\u2082 to acetyl thioesters, suggesting either a single environment with diverse microenvironments or a multi-setting scenario.\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents** (Lost City-type: 40\u2013120\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311, H\u2082 up to 14 mM, continuous for >100,000 years) are optimal for the initial CO\u2082 reduction steps. Serpentinization generates both the reductant (H\u2082) and the catalyst (awaruite, magnetite, greigite) simultaneously. The pH gradient across FeS/NiS membranes (~5 units on Hadean Earth) provides an electrochemical driving force of 250\u2013300 mV \u2014 sufficient to power CO\u2082 reduction to CO and formate. Microporous inorganic compartments within chimney structures solve the concentration problem while providing proto-cellular confinement (Russell and Hall, 1997). However, thioester stability is severely limited under these conditions: **methyl thioacetate half-life at pH 10, 100\u00b0C is only ~43 seconds** (Mayer et al., 2024, *iScience*), compared to **155 days at pH 7, 23\u00b0C** (Brosnan et al., 2011, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*). This stability constraint strongly favors thioester accumulation in **cooler, more acidic microenvironments** \u2014 perhaps at the ocean-facing exterior of vent structures where mixing with acidic seawater moderates both temperature and pH.\n\n**Surface evaporitic pools** and terrestrial hot springs favor condensation and polymerization steps. Wet-dry cycling drives anhydride and thioester bond formation during drying phases. UV irradiation provides photochemical energy for radical reactions, including pyruvate oxidative decarboxylation to acetyl thioesters (Leqraa et al., 2020). Nan et al. (2024, *Nature Communications*) demonstrated FeS-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to methanol at 80\u2013120\u00b0C in conditions mimicking terrestrial hot springs, with UV-visible light enhancing activity. **Thermophoresis** in rock pore networks can selectively accumulate diverse prebiotic building blocks through temperature gradients (Matreux et al., 2024).\n\n---\n\n## Unresolved challenges and the path forward\n\nDespite remarkable experimental progress, several fundamental problems remain.\n\n**The CoA complexity gap** is perhaps the most significant. Acetyl-CoA is a large, information-rich molecule containing pantothenic acid, \u03b2-alanine, cysteamine, and 3'-phospho-ADP \u2014 each component presenting its own prebiotic synthesis challenge. However, three developments have substantially narrowed this gap. First, **Fairchild et al. (2024, *Science* 383: 911\u2013918)** achieved the first prebiotically plausible synthesis of pantetheine \u2014 CoA's catalytically active subunit \u2014 through chemoselective nitrile chemistry in water at room temperature, dramatically outperforming Miller's earlier attempt (Keefe, Newton, and Miller, 1995, *Nature*). Second, Goldford et al. (2017, *Cell*) computationally demonstrated that substituting pantetheine for CoA maintains network viability in a phosphate-free proto-metabolism. Third, even simpler thiols \u2014 methanethiol, cysteamine, coenzyme M (HSCH\u2082CH\u2082SO\u2083\u207b) \u2014 can serve the same chemical function, as demonstrated by near-quantitative aminoacyl-thiol yields using coenzyme M (Singh et al., 2025, *Nature*).\n\n**The concentration problem** persists for dilute products in open aqueous environments. Proposed solutions include microporous vent confinement, thermophoretic accumulation in rock fissures, wet-dry cycling in surface pools, eutectic concentration in ice, and the remarkable **10\u2076-fold concentration** achievable in green rust interlayers. Thiol-thioester exchange (k = 1.7 M\u207b\u00b9s\u207b\u00b9 at pH 7, 23\u00b0C) is several orders of magnitude faster than thioester hydrolysis, meaning that even dilute thioester pools can efficiently transfer their acetyl groups to new thiol acceptors before being lost to hydrolysis.\n\n**Selectivity and the \"chemical mess\" problem** \u2014 the tendency of prebiotic reactions to produce complex mixtures of products rather than the specific molecules biology uses \u2014 remains a core challenge. Mineral surfaces provide some selectivity through preferential adsorption and oriented catalysis, but lack the precise substrate positioning of enzyme active sites. The emerging \"systems chemistry\" approach (Sutherland, Powner) addresses this by identifying reaction networks where selectivity emerges from the interplay of multiple concurrent reactions rather than from any single selective step.\n\n**The mineral-to-enzyme transition** \u2014 how catalysis migrated from mineral surfaces to soluble iron-sulfur clusters to metalloproteins \u2014 is incompletely understood. Jordan et al.'s demonstration of spontaneous [4Fe-4S] cluster self-assembly from simple precursors and Wilson et al.'s synthesis of heterometallic [NiFe\u2084S\u2084] clusters provide critical missing pieces, but the full trajectory from greigite surfaces to CODH/ACS holoenzyme remains speculative. Notably, the redox bifunctionality of nickel (cycling between Ni\u2070/Ni\u00b9\u207a/Ni\u00b2\u207a/Ni\u00b3\u207a) that is essential for ACS catalysis has not been observed in natural nickel-bearing minerals \u2014 only under imposed electrochemical conditions \u2014 raising questions about whether mineral catalysis alone could have supported the full carbonylation mechanism.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of acetyl thioesters has progressed from theoretical proposals to experimentally demonstrated chemistry achieving yields comparable to enzymatic reactions. The field has converged on a core insight: **the same nickel-iron-sulfide chemistry that catalyzes acetyl-CoA synthesis in the most ancient biological pathway also operates on mineral surfaces under geologically realistic conditions**. The structural identity between greigite [Fe\u2084S\u2084] units and ferredoxin clusters, and between Ni-doped iron sulfides and CODH/ACS active sites, is not merely analogical but reflects a direct evolutionary continuity from geochemistry to biochemistry. The most productive current direction combines the Strasbourg group's native-metal CO\u2082 reduction chemistry with the Kitadai group's geoelectrochemical thioester synthesis and the Powner group's prebiotic CoA-precursor synthesis \u2014 together these define a plausible, experimentally grounded pathway from volcanic gases to the central energy-coupling molecule of all life. The critical next milestone is demonstrating a complete, continuous sequence from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 to an acetyl thioester in a single geochemically realistic reactor \u2014 a goal that, given the pace of recent advances, appears increasingly within reach.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Acetyl-CoA\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network follows literature-grounded prebiotic acetyl-thioester chemistry in which hydrothermal CO2 reduction produces the key C1 and C2 hubs formate, CO, acetate, and pyruvate; surface cyanosulfidic and UV-driven chemistry supplies additional pyruvate and stabilizing concentration environments; and biochemical/prebiotic assembly connects methyl thioacetate, acetyl phosphate, pantetheine, and cysteamine to a proto-acetyl-CoA endpoint. Because the literature shows stronger support for prebiotic acetyl thioesters than for full coenzyme A, the target is represented as an acetyl-CoA/pantetheine-thioester endpoint assembled from experimentally supported subunits, with explicit acknowledgment that the final transfer to full CoA remains the least certain step. Ten distinct pathways converge through hub molecules CO, formate, pyruvate, methyl thioacetate, and acetyl phosphate.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3SH\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanethiol\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methyl mercaptan\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4S/c1-2/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetate/acetic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2,4H,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"S-methyl ethanethioate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methyl thioacetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6OS/c1-3(4)5-2/h1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H5O5P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetyl phosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetyl phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H5O5P/c1-2(3)7-8(4,5)6/h1H3,(H2,4,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C11H22N2O4S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,4-dihydroxy-3,3-dimethyl-N-(2-sulfanylethyl)butanamide linked to beta-alanine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pantetheine\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H7NS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminoethane-1-thiol\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cysteamine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H7NS/c3-1-2-4/h4H,1-3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C23H38N7O17P3S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetyl coenzyme A\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Acetyl-CoA\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Greigite/awaruite-catalyzed reduction of CO2 to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"awaruite (Ni3Fe)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"100\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"alkaline hydrothermal, H2/CO2; geologically realistic pressurized reactor\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and awaruite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline solution; hydrothermal vent analog\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface H2 activation and CO2 hydrogenation yield formate as the first stable reduced C1 product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Preiner et al. (2020) reported formate production up to 200 mM from H2 + CO2 using hydrothermal minerals including greigite and awaruite at 100\u00b0C, matching the proposed Wood-Ljungdahl-like hydrothermal entry step; Russell and Martin (2007) provide the vent pH-gradient framework.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"NiFe-sulfide geoelectrochemical reduction of CO2 to surface-bound CO\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient to hydrothermal interface\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"partially reduced NiS with FeS/NiS context\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"neutral pH; -0.6 to -1.0 V vs SHE geoelectrochemical conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electroreduction of CO2 on partially reduced nickel sulfide produces accumulated surface CO poised for carbonylation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kitadai et al. (2021) showed NiS_PERM under geoelectrochemical conditions accumulates surface-bound CO from CO2 electroreduction and then drives methyl thioacetate synthesis; Roldan et al. (2015) supports FeS/greigite CO2-reduction behavior.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal abiotic formation or delivery of methanethiol\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"40-120\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"hydrothermal\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/FeS2 sulfide surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"sulfide-rich, anoxic fluids; methanethiol also documented in hydrothermal fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sulfide-rich hydrothermal mineral surfaces support reduced sulfur organic species, including methanethiol, or concentrate hydrothermally supplied methanethiol for downstream thioester chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research summary states methanethiol is present in modern hydrothermal fluids and can be generated abiotically in sulfide-rich environments; Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997) used methanethiol as the thiol substrate in NiS/FeS-mediated thioester synthesis; W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1988) provides the iron-sulfur world rationale. This node represents a literature-supported feedstock step rather than a single fully resolved reaction.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Native iron reduction of CO2 to acetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"30-100\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1-40 bar CO2\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"native Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic aqueous CO2 reduction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Direct electron transfer from Fe0 reduces CO2 to multi-carbon products including acetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Varma et al. (2018) demonstrated direct reduction of CO2 by native iron to acetate, pyruvate, and formate at 30-100\u00b0C and 1-40 bar CO2; Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (2019) place acetate-generating ketoacid chemistry into a wider proto-metabolic network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal mineral synthesis of pyruvate from H2 and CO2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"100\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"alkaline hydrothermal reactor\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite, magnetite, awaruite-like vent minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline solution under H2/CO2\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Successive mineral-mediated reductions and C-C bond formation in a Wood-Ljungdahl-like network generate pyruvate as a low-yield but central branch-point product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Preiner et al. (2020) observed pyruvate formation from H2 + CO2 using greigite, magnetite, and awaruite at 100\u00b0C; Beyazay et al. (2023) extended similar product spectra to 25\u00b0C under 25 bar with Ni3Fe nanoparticles.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"High-pressure organometallic FeS-carbonyl synthesis of pyruvate from CO and thiol\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"250\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"50-200 MPa\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS organometallic carbonyl phases\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"deep hydrothermal high-pressure simulation with alkyl thiols\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO and thiol interact with FeS to form organometallic iron-sulfur-carbonyl intermediates that yield pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cody et al. (2000) demonstrated pyruvic acid synthesis from CO + FeS + alkyl thiols at 250\u00b0C and 50-200 MPa, explicitly linking hydrothermal organometallic chemistry to CODH/ACS-like intermediates.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic photochemical route to pyruvate via alpha-hydroxy acid oxidation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photoredox with sulfide mineral and photocatalytic surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation; cyanosulfidic setting in shallow surface waters\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN-derived carbohydrate intermediates furnish alpha-hydroxy acids whose UV-driven oxidation gives pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) established cyanosulfidic protometabolism from HCN and sulfide under UV; Ritson (2021) reported pyruvate formation in about 14% yield through UV-driven oxidation of alpha-hydroxy acids. The mineral specification is included to satisfy the required surface-agent field while remaining consistent with photoredox surface settings.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"NiS/FeS carbonylation of methanethiol to methyl thioacetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"100\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1.05 bar CO\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"coprecipitated NiS/FeS\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"sealed anaerobic vials; initial pH about 8; 7 days in original demonstration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nickel-sulfide surface binds CO and methyl-thiol equivalents, enabling migratory insertion to an acetyl intermediate followed by thioester release as methyl thioacetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997) provided the foundational demonstration of methyl thioacetate formation from CO and methanethiol on NiS/FeS at 100\u00b0C; W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1988) proposed the underlying iron-sulfur world carbonylation mechanism.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Geoelectrochemical room-temperature synthesis of methyl thioacetate from surface CO and methanethiol\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient to vent-interface\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"partially reduced NiS (NiS_PERM), optionally coprecipitated with CoS\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"neutral pH; geoelectrochemical potential -0.6 to -1.0 V vs SHE; up to 35% yield, 56% with CoS\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electroreduced nickel sulfide accumulates CO from CO2 reduction and then couples it with methanethiol to release methyl thioacetate under mild conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kitadai et al. (2021) reported room-temperature, neutral-pH geoelectrochemical methyl thioacetate synthesis with up to 35% yield from NiS_PERM and up to 56% with CoS coprecipitation, a major improvement over Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-driven oxidative decarboxylative thioesterification of pyruvate to thioacetate ester\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV irradiation on mineral-rich drying surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"surface photochemical conditions; no external oxidant required in disulfide version\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes UV-promoted oxidative decarboxylation to an acetyl equivalent that is trapped by sulfur nucleophiles to form thioacetate ester.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Leqraa et al. (2020) demonstrated that pyruvate reacts with disulfides under UV irradiation to yield thioacetate esters without external oxidant, directly bridging pyruvate-centered surface chemistry to thioester metabolism. This network uses methanethiol as the sulfur acceptor node to connect established thiol chemistry; this adaptation is a minimal connector based on the reported thioacetate-ester formation logic.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Thioester-phosphate exchange to acetyl phosphate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"23-50\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"requires inorganic phosphate in solution; favored in cooler, near-neutral microenvironments\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetyl transfer from thioester to inorganic phosphate yields acetyl phosphate as a higher phosphoryl-transfer-potential intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Martin and Russell (2007) argued acetyl phosphate as primordial energy currency and the research summary explicitly notes non-enzymatic formation of acetyl phosphate from acetyl thioesters and inorganic phosphate; de Duve (1991) supports the energetic centrality of thioesters. This is a literature-grounded connecting step, though the exact substrate scope from methyl thioacetate is less directly quantified than the general principle.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Prebiotic aqueous synthesis of pantetheine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"chemoselective nitrile chemistry in water\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aqueous nitrile-based assembly furnishes the catalytically active pantetheine subunit of coenzyme A.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fairchild, Islam, Singh, and Powner (2024) reported the first prebiotically plausible synthesis of pantetheine in water at room temperature, substantially narrowing the CoA complexity gap.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Thiolation transfer from methyl thioacetate to cysteamine yielding acetylated thiol equivalent\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"23-40\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"near-neutral pH where thiol-thioester exchange outcompetes hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fast thiol-thioester exchange transfers the acetyl-capable thioester functionality between sulfur acceptors, linking simple thioesters to more complex biological thiols.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research summary notes thiol-thioester exchange (k = 1.7 M^-1 s^-1 at pH 7, 23\u00b0C) is much faster than thioester hydrolysis, allowing acetyl transfer among thiol acceptors. Brosnan et al. (2011) support thioester stability at neutral, cooler conditions. This reaction is explicitly a connector step motivated by the literature's exchange chemistry rather than a direct named experimental pantetheine-acylation report.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Assembly of acetyl-CoA from acetyl donor and pantetheine-like thiol scaffold\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"23-40\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"proto-biochemical pool; represents late-stage cofactor completion beyond directly demonstrated full prebiotic CoA assembly\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetyl transfer from activated acetyl phosphate or equivalent thioester donor to a pantetheine-containing cofactor scaffold yields the acetyl-CoA endpoint.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Goldford et al. (2017) showed pantetheine can substitute functionally for CoA in phosphate-free protometabolic networks, and Fairchild et al. (2024) established prebiotic access to pantetheine. The complete assembly of full acetyl-CoA remains unresolved in the literature and is therefore explicitly speculative but necessary to connect experimentally supported acetyl-thioester chemistry to the requested target molecule.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Iron-sulfur world direct carbonylation route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is reduced to CO and hydrothermal methanethiol is carbonylated on NiS/FeS-like sulfide surfaces to methyl thioacetate, then converted through acetyl phosphate into the target endpoint.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Geoelectrochemical vent thioester route\",\n      \"description\": \"Electroreduced NiS produces surface CO from CO2 and drives room-temperature methyl thioacetate formation before late-stage biochemical assembly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate to surface thioester route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal H2/CO2 chemistry generates pyruvate, which is exported to surface UV environments and converted to thioacetate ester, then to acetyl phosphate and the target.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cody high-pressure pyruvate branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Deep hydrothermal CO plus thiol chemistry on FeS yields pyruvate at high pressure, followed by surface oxidative decarboxylative thioesterification and late-stage assembly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic pyruvate route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic chemistry produces pyruvate, which enters UV-mediated thioester formation and biochemical acetyl transfer steps.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Native iron acetate-first route\",\n      \"description\": \"Native Fe0 reduces CO2 to acetate; acetate is treated as part of the same acetyl-pool feeding activated acetyl chemistry through methyl thioacetate and acetyl phosphate convergence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-to-CO vent convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formate production marks the methyl branch entry, converging with CO generation and methanethiol carbonylation to methyl thioacetate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Pantetheine-assisted thioester exchange route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal methyl thioacetate is coupled to a prebiotically formed pantetheine-like thiol pool through exchange chemistry before final acetyl-CoA assembly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface-to-biochemical pantetheine convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface pyruvate generation converges with independently synthesized pantetheine, joining activated acetyl chemistry to a cofactor precursor scaffold.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Thiol-exchange mediated late transfer route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal methyl thioacetate transfers acetyl potential through rapid thiol-thioester exchange into a pantetheine/cysteamine sulfur network that culminates in acetyl-CoA.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_005\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Acetyl-CoA", "overall_strategy": "This network follows literature-grounded prebiotic acetyl-thioester chemistry in which hydrothermal CO2 reduction produces the key C1 and C2 hubs formate, CO, acetate, and pyruvate; surface cyanosulfidic and UV-driven chemistry supplies additional pyruvate and stabilizing concentration environments; and biochemical/prebiotic assembly connects methyl thioacetate, acetyl phosphate, pantetheine, and cysteamine to a proto-acetyl-CoA endpoint. Because the literature shows stronger support for prebiotic acetyl thioesters than for full coenzyme A, the target is represented as an acetyl-CoA/pantetheine-thioester endpoint assembled from experimentally supported subunits, with explicit acknowledgment that the final transfer to full CoA remains the least certain step. Ten distinct pathways converge through hub molecules CO, formate, pyruvate, methyl thioacetate, and acetyl phosphate.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "HCOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH3SH", "iupac_name": "methanethiol", "common_name": "methyl mercaptan", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4S/c1-2/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "acetic acid", "common_name": "acetate/acetic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanoic acid", "common_name": "lactic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2,4H,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H6O2S", "iupac_name": "S-methyl ethanethioate", "common_name": "methyl thioacetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6OS/c1-3(4)5-2/h1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C2H5O5P", "iupac_name": "acetyl phosphate", "common_name": "acetyl phosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5O5P/c1-2(3)7-8(4,5)6/h1H3,(H2,4,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C11H22N2O4S", "iupac_name": "2,4-dihydroxy-3,3-dimethyl-N-(2-sulfanylethyl)butanamide linked to beta-alanine", "common_name": "pantetheine", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C2H7NS", "iupac_name": "2-aminoethane-1-thiol", "common_name": "cysteamine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H7NS/c3-1-2-4/h4H,1-3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C23H38N7O17P3S", "iupac_name": "acetyl coenzyme A", "common_name": "Acetyl-CoA", "inchi": null, "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Greigite/awaruite-catalyzed reduction of CO2 to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "awaruite (Ni3Fe)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "100\u00b0C", "pressure": "alkaline hydrothermal, H2/CO2; geologically realistic pressurized reactor", "catalyst": "greigite and awaruite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline solution; hydrothermal vent analog"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface H2 activation and CO2 hydrogenation yield formate as the first stable reduced C1 product.", "reasoning": "Preiner et al. (2020) reported formate production up to 200 mM from H2 + CO2 using hydrothermal minerals including greigite and awaruite at 100\u00b0C, matching the proposed Wood-Ljungdahl-like hydrothermal entry step; Russell and Martin (2007) provide the vent pH-gradient framework."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "NiFe-sulfide geoelectrochemical reduction of CO2 to surface-bound CO", "inputs": ["mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "ambient to hydrothermal interface", "catalyst": "partially reduced NiS with FeS/NiS context", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral pH; -0.6 to -1.0 V vs SHE geoelectrochemical conditions"}, "mechanism": "Electroreduction of CO2 on partially reduced nickel sulfide produces accumulated surface CO poised for carbonylation.", "reasoning": "Kitadai et al. (2021) showed NiS_PERM under geoelectrochemical conditions accumulates surface-bound CO from CO2 electroreduction and then drives methyl thioacetate synthesis; Roldan et al. (2015) supports FeS/greigite CO2-reduction behavior."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal abiotic formation or delivery of methanethiol", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "40-120\u00b0C", "pressure": "hydrothermal", "catalyst": "FeS/FeS2 sulfide surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "sulfide-rich, anoxic fluids; methanethiol also documented in hydrothermal fluids"}, "mechanism": "Sulfide-rich hydrothermal mineral surfaces support reduced sulfur organic species, including methanethiol, or concentrate hydrothermally supplied methanethiol for downstream thioester chemistry.", "reasoning": "The research summary states methanethiol is present in modern hydrothermal fluids and can be generated abiotically in sulfide-rich environments; Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997) used methanethiol as the thiol substrate in NiS/FeS-mediated thioester synthesis; W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1988) provides the iron-sulfur world rationale. This node represents a literature-supported feedstock step rather than a single fully resolved reaction."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Native iron reduction of CO2 to acetate", "inputs": ["mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "30-100\u00b0C", "pressure": "1-40 bar CO2", "catalyst": "native Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic aqueous CO2 reduction"}, "mechanism": "Direct electron transfer from Fe0 reduces CO2 to multi-carbon products including acetate.", "reasoning": "Varma et al. (2018) demonstrated direct reduction of CO2 by native iron to acetate, pyruvate, and formate at 30-100\u00b0C and 1-40 bar CO2; Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (2019) place acetate-generating ketoacid chemistry into a wider proto-metabolic network."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrothermal mineral synthesis of pyruvate from H2 and CO2", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "100\u00b0C", "pressure": "alkaline hydrothermal reactor", "catalyst": "greigite, magnetite, awaruite-like vent minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline solution under H2/CO2"}, "mechanism": "Successive mineral-mediated reductions and C-C bond formation in a Wood-Ljungdahl-like network generate pyruvate as a low-yield but central branch-point product.", "reasoning": "Preiner et al. (2020) observed pyruvate formation from H2 + CO2 using greigite, magnetite, and awaruite at 100\u00b0C; Beyazay et al. (2023) extended similar product spectra to 25\u00b0C under 25 bar with Ni3Fe nanoparticles."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "High-pressure organometallic FeS-carbonyl synthesis of pyruvate from CO and thiol", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "250\u00b0C", "pressure": "50-200 MPa", "catalyst": "FeS organometallic carbonyl phases", "aqueous": "true", "other": "deep hydrothermal high-pressure simulation with alkyl thiols"}, "mechanism": "CO and thiol interact with FeS to form organometallic iron-sulfur-carbonyl intermediates that yield pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Cody et al. (2000) demonstrated pyruvic acid synthesis from CO + FeS + alkyl thiols at 250\u00b0C and 50-200 MPa, explicitly linking hydrothermal organometallic chemistry to CODH/ACS-like intermediates."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photochemical route to pyruvate via alpha-hydroxy acid oxidation", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox with sulfide mineral and photocatalytic surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; cyanosulfidic setting in shallow surface waters"}, "mechanism": "HCN-derived carbohydrate intermediates furnish alpha-hydroxy acids whose UV-driven oxidation gives pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) established cyanosulfidic protometabolism from HCN and sulfide under UV; Ritson (2021) reported pyruvate formation in about 14% yield through UV-driven oxidation of alpha-hydroxy acids. The mineral specification is included to satisfy the required surface-agent field while remaining consistent with photoredox surface settings."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "NiS/FeS carbonylation of methanethiol to methyl thioacetate", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "100\u00b0C", "pressure": "1.05 bar CO", "catalyst": "coprecipitated NiS/FeS", "aqueous": "true", "other": "sealed anaerobic vials; initial pH about 8; 7 days in original demonstration"}, "mechanism": "Nickel-sulfide surface binds CO and methyl-thiol equivalents, enabling migratory insertion to an acetyl intermediate followed by thioester release as methyl thioacetate.", "reasoning": "Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997) provided the foundational demonstration of methyl thioacetate formation from CO and methanethiol on NiS/FeS at 100\u00b0C; W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1988) proposed the underlying iron-sulfur world carbonylation mechanism."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Geoelectrochemical room-temperature synthesis of methyl thioacetate from surface CO and methanethiol", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "ambient to vent-interface", "catalyst": "partially reduced NiS (NiS_PERM), optionally coprecipitated with CoS", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral pH; geoelectrochemical potential -0.6 to -1.0 V vs SHE; up to 35% yield, 56% with CoS"}, "mechanism": "Electroreduced nickel sulfide accumulates CO from CO2 reduction and then couples it with methanethiol to release methyl thioacetate under mild conditions.", "reasoning": "Kitadai et al. (2021) reported room-temperature, neutral-pH geoelectrochemical methyl thioacetate synthesis with up to 35% yield from NiS_PERM and up to 56% with CoS coprecipitation, a major improvement over Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "UV-driven oxidative decarboxylative thioesterification of pyruvate to thioacetate ester", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV irradiation on mineral-rich drying surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "surface photochemical conditions; no external oxidant required in disulfide version"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes UV-promoted oxidative decarboxylation to an acetyl equivalent that is trapped by sulfur nucleophiles to form thioacetate ester.", "reasoning": "Leqraa et al. (2020) demonstrated that pyruvate reacts with disulfides under UV irradiation to yield thioacetate esters without external oxidant, directly bridging pyruvate-centered surface chemistry to thioester metabolism. This network uses methanethiol as the sulfur acceptor node to connect established thiol chemistry; this adaptation is a minimal connector based on the reported thioacetate-ester formation logic."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Thioester-phosphate exchange to acetyl phosphate", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "23-50\u00b0C", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "requires inorganic phosphate in solution; favored in cooler, near-neutral microenvironments"}, "mechanism": "Acetyl transfer from thioester to inorganic phosphate yields acetyl phosphate as a higher phosphoryl-transfer-potential intermediate.", "reasoning": "Martin and Russell (2007) argued acetyl phosphate as primordial energy currency and the research summary explicitly notes non-enzymatic formation of acetyl phosphate from acetyl thioesters and inorganic phosphate; de Duve (1991) supports the energetic centrality of thioesters. This is a literature-grounded connecting step, though the exact substrate scope from methyl thioacetate is less directly quantified than the general principle."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Prebiotic aqueous synthesis of pantetheine", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "chemoselective nitrile chemistry in water"}, "mechanism": "Aqueous nitrile-based assembly furnishes the catalytically active pantetheine subunit of coenzyme A.", "reasoning": "Fairchild, Islam, Singh, and Powner (2024) reported the first prebiotically plausible synthesis of pantetheine in water at room temperature, substantially narrowing the CoA complexity gap."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Thiolation transfer from methyl thioacetate to cysteamine yielding acetylated thiol equivalent", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "23-40\u00b0C", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "near-neutral pH where thiol-thioester exchange outcompetes hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Fast thiol-thioester exchange transfers the acetyl-capable thioester functionality between sulfur acceptors, linking simple thioesters to more complex biological thiols.", "reasoning": "The research summary notes thiol-thioester exchange (k = 1.7 M^-1 s^-1 at pH 7, 23\u00b0C) is much faster than thioester hydrolysis, allowing acetyl transfer among thiol acceptors. Brosnan et al. (2011) support thioester stability at neutral, cooler conditions. This reaction is explicitly a connector step motivated by the literature's exchange chemistry rather than a direct named experimental pantetheine-acylation report."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Assembly of acetyl-CoA from acetyl donor and pantetheine-like thiol scaffold", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "23-40\u00b0C", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "proto-biochemical pool; represents late-stage cofactor completion beyond directly demonstrated full prebiotic CoA assembly"}, "mechanism": "Acetyl transfer from activated acetyl phosphate or equivalent thioester donor to a pantetheine-containing cofactor scaffold yields the acetyl-CoA endpoint.", "reasoning": "Goldford et al. (2017) showed pantetheine can substitute functionally for CoA in phosphate-free protometabolic networks, and Fairchild et al. (2024) established prebiotic access to pantetheine. The complete assembly of full acetyl-CoA remains unresolved in the literature and is therefore explicitly speculative but necessary to connect experimentally supported acetyl-thioester chemistry to the requested target molecule."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Iron-sulfur world direct carbonylation route", "description": "CO2 is reduced to CO and hydrothermal methanethiol is carbonylated on NiS/FeS-like sulfide surfaces to methyl thioacetate, then converted through acetyl phosphate into the target endpoint.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Geoelectrochemical vent thioester route", "description": "Electroreduced NiS produces surface CO from CO2 and drives room-temperature methyl thioacetate formation before late-stage biochemical assembly.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate to surface thioester route", "description": "Hydrothermal H2/CO2 chemistry generates pyruvate, which is exported to surface UV environments and converted to thioacetate ester, then to acetyl phosphate and the target.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Cody high-pressure pyruvate branch", "description": "Deep hydrothermal CO plus thiol chemistry on FeS yields pyruvate at high pressure, followed by surface oxidative decarboxylative thioesterification and late-stage assembly.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_007", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Cyanosulfidic pyruvate route", "description": "Surface cyanosulfidic chemistry produces pyruvate, which enters UV-mediated thioester formation and biochemical acetyl transfer steps.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_007", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Native iron acetate-first route", "description": "Native Fe0 reduces CO2 to acetate; acetate is treated as part of the same acetyl-pool feeding activated acetyl chemistry through methyl thioacetate and acetyl phosphate convergence.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_003", "rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_005", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Formate-to-CO vent convergence route", "description": "Hydrothermal formate production marks the methyl branch entry, converging with CO generation and methanethiol carbonylation to methyl thioacetate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Pantetheine-assisted thioester exchange route", "description": "Hydrothermal methyl thioacetate is coupled to a prebiotically formed pantetheine-like thiol pool through exchange chemistry before final acetyl-CoA assembly.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_009", "rxn_012", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Surface-to-biochemical pantetheine convergence route", "description": "Surface pyruvate generation converges with independently synthesized pantetheine, joining activated acetyl chemistry to a cofactor precursor scaffold.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_007", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_011", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Thiol-exchange mediated late transfer route", "description": "Hydrothermal methyl thioacetate transfers acetyl potential through rapid thiol-thioester exchange into a pantetheine/cysteamine sulfur network that culminates in acetyl-CoA.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_008", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_015", "mol_014"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_004", "mol_007", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_005"], "convergence_poin