etheine\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C23H38N7O17P3S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-[(3-{[2-(3-{[(3aS,4R,6R,6aR)-6-(6-amino-9H-purin-9-yl)-4-hydroxy-2,2-dimethyltetrahydrofuro[3,4-d][1,3,2]dioxaphosphinin-3-yl]oxy}-2-hydroxyethyl)amino]-3-oxopropyl]sulfanyl}ethyl)carbamoyl]-3,3-dimethyl-4-oxobutyl dihydrogen triphosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"coenzyme A\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C21H36N7O16P3S/c1-21(2,17(31)8-30)18(32)26-5-4-48-7-6-25-16(29)3-9-44-47(41,42)45-46(39,40)43-10-15-13(28)12(34)20(38-15)27-11-22-14-19(23)24-18/h11-15,28,34H,3-10H2,1-2H3,(H,25,29)(H,26,32)(H,39,40)(H,41,42)(H2,22,23,24)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C23H38N7O17P3S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetyl coenzyme A\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Acetyl-CoA\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate on greigite/magnetite/awaruite analog surfaces\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"alkaline hydrothermal, H2/CO2; reported at elevated pressure in sealed reactors\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite, magnetite; hydrothermal mineral systems including Ni3Fe/awaruite analogs\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline solution; vent-like conditions; formate up to 200 mM reported\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-catalyzed hydrogenation/electroreduction of CO2 gives the first stable C1 product, formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Preiner et al. (2020) showed greigite, magnetite, and awaruite catalyze H2 + CO2 conversion to formate, acetate, methanol, and pyruvate at 100C under alkaline hydrothermal conditions; this implements the first stable reduction step emphasized by Russell and Martin (2007).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to carbon monoxide on Ni-Fe sulfide surfaces\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni-bearing FeS/greigite-like sulfide surfaces under vent redox gradients\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent micropores; pH gradient about 3-5 units; geoelectrochemical driving force about 250-300 mV\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 is electroreduced on Ni-Fe sulfide surfaces to surface-bound or dissolved CO, analogous to CODH chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Wachtershauser (1988) proposed CO generation on FeS/NiS surfaces as part of surface metabolism; Russell (1994) and Martin & Russell (2007) framed alkaline vent CO2-to-CO reduction as a Wood-Ljungdahl analog. Kitadai et al. (2021) directly observed CO accumulation on partially reduced NiS under geoelectrochemical conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Native iron reduction of CO2 to acetate and pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"303-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1-40 bar CO2\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"native iron\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic; direct CO2 reduction by Fe0 without biological electron bifurcation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Oxidation of Fe0 provides reducing equivalents that drive CO2 fixation to formate, acetate, and pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Varma et al. (2018) showed Fe0 reduces CO2 to acetate, pyruvate, and formate at 30-100C under 1-40 bar CO2. This route is a major literature-supported convergent source of both acetate and pyruvate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from H2 and CO2 on greigite/magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"hydrothermal reactor pressure\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline conditions; pyruvate detected at low micromolar levels\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential mineral-catalyzed C1 reduction and C-C bond formation yields pyruvate as part of a nonenzymatic Wood-Ljungdahl/rTCA-like product network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Preiner et al. (2020) reported pyruvate formation from H2 + CO2 on greigite, magnetite, and awaruite at 100C, directly supporting hydrothermal production of this hub metabolite.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"High-pressure FeS-carbonyl pyruvate synthesis from CO and thiols\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"523K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"50-200 MPa\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"iron sulfide organometallic phase\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"deep hydrothermal high-pressure system; alkyl thiols required\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO reacts with FeS and alkyl thiols to generate organometallic Fe-S-carbonyl intermediates that yield pyruvic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cody et al. (2000) demonstrated pyruvate synthesis from CO + FeS + alkyl thiols at 250C and 50-200 MPa, providing a distinct hydrothermal route to pyruvate through organometallic intermediates.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic surface synthesis of pyruvate precursor network\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photoredox with sulfide minerals and photocatalytic mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"HCN/H2S-driven cyanosulfidic chemistry under UV irradiation; precursor pooling step representing documented systems chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN-based photoredox chemistry builds activated nitrile intermediates that feed into pyruvate-forming surface networks.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) established cyanosulfidic protometabolism from HCN and H2S under UV photoredox conditions. This reaction is included as a connecting precursor step because the supplied literature identifies the Sutherland framework as the source of pyruvate-forming surface chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-driven surface formation of pyruvate from cyanosulfidic alpha-hydroxy acid network\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photochemistry on mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanosulfidic photoredox regime; pyruvate reported in about 14% yield from alpha-hydroxy acid oxidation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven oxidation within the cyanosulfidic network converts alpha-hydroxy acid precursors into pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson (2021) reported UV-driven formation of pyruvate in the Sutherland-style cyanosulfidic network at about 14% yield; Patel et al. (2015) provides the broader systems chemistry context. This is the surface branch to the pyruvate hub.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal NiS/FeS carbonylation of methanethiol to S-methyl thioacetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1.05 bar CO\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"NiS/FeS coprecipitates on sulfide mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"sealed anaerobic vials; initial pH about 8; 7 days for mixed sulfides, 20 h for NiS alone\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO binds Ni centers, methyl-thiol activation generates Ni-CH3 equivalents, migratory insertion forms an acetyl intermediate, and thiolysis releases S-methyl thioacetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Huber & Wachtershauser (1997) experimentally demonstrated methyl thioacetate formation from CO and methanethiol on NiS/FeS at 100C, establishing the core prebiotic acetyl thioester synthesis route.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Room-temperature geoelectrochemical synthesis of S-methyl thioacetate on partially reduced NiS\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient to hydrothermal electrochemical interface\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"partially reduced NiS (NiS_PERM), optionally with CoS\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"neutral pH; electrochemical potential from -0.6 to -1.0 V vs SHE; surface CO accumulation; up to 35% yield, 56% with CoS\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 is electroreduced to surface-bound CO on partially reduced Ni sulfides, followed by carbonylation of methanethiol to S-methyl thioacetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kitadai et al. (2021) showed NiS_PERM formed under geoelectrochemical conditions catalyzes methyl thioacetate synthesis at room temperature and neutral pH with greatly improved yields. This is the strongest direct literature route to the thioester hub.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"UV decarboxylative thioesterification of pyruvate with disulfide to thioacetate ester\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV irradiation with mineral-assisted concentration/photochemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic surface pool; disulfide-based sulfur donor required; no external oxidant\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes UV-driven oxidative decarboxylation in the presence of disulfides to yield activated thioacetate esters.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Leqraa et al. (2020) demonstrated that pyruvate reacts with disulfides under UV irradiation to form thioacetate esters without an external oxidant. The network uses dimethyl disulfide as the sulfur-state-correct precursor to S-methyl thioacetate, correcting earlier over-simplification.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Thioester-phosphate exchange from S-methyl thioacetate to acetyl phosphate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\", \"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-323K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"requires inorganic phosphate in neutral to mildly alkaline aqueous solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic phosphate attack on the thioester carbonyl transfers the acetyl group from sulfur to phosphate, generating acetyl phosphate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Martin & Russell (2007) emphasized acetyl phosphate as a plausible primordial energy currency formed from acetyl thioesters and inorganic phosphate. The supplied literature explicitly identifies acetyl phosphate as a bridge between thioester and phosphate metabolism.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Prebiotic synthesis of pantetheine from nitrile-based precursor chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted concentration/stabilization\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"room-temperature aqueous chemoselective nitrile chemistry; multistep network condensed to preserve connectivity\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile-based aqueous chemistry constructs the pantetheine scaffold as the catalytically active CoA subunit.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fairchild et al. (2024) reported the first prebiotically plausible synthesis of pantetheine through chemoselective nitrile chemistry in water at room temperature. This reaction is intentionally compressed as a literature-grounded network summary, not as a claim of direct one-step conversion from HCN alone.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Thiol-thioester exchange between S-methyl thioacetate and pantetheine to form acetyl pantetheine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\", \"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"296-323K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"neutral pH favored; thiol-thioester exchange outcompetes hydrolysis on suitable timescales\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pantetheine thiol attacks the thioester carbonyl of S-methyl thioacetate, transferring the acetyl group and releasing methanethiol.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied literature notes that thiol-thioester exchange is substantially faster than thioester hydrolysis and that pantetheine can replace CoA in proto-metabolic network models (Goldford et al., 2017; Brosnan et al., 2011 as summarized in the report). This step yields an acetyl-pantetheine proto-cofactor rather than incorrectly claiming pantetheine synthesis from simple thiols.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Speculative late-stage conversion of acetyl pantetheine and CoA framework to acetyl-CoA\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\", \"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-323K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"thiol-thioester exchange in concentrated prebiotic pools or interfaces; speculative because full CoA prebiotic assembly remains unresolved\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetyl transfer by thiol-thioester exchange from acetyl pantetheine to a CoA-like thiol acceptor gives acetyl-CoA.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is explicitly speculative and included only to connect the literature-supported acetyl-thioester network to the requested target molecule. The research report states that the CoA complexity gap remains unresolved, while Fairchild et al. (2024) narrows the gap via pantetheine synthesis. Therefore the network treats full acetyl-CoA formation as an open problem rather than an established prebiotic reaction.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Wachtershauser iron-sulfur carbonylation route\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct hydrothermal thioester synthesis from CO2-derived CO and methanethiol on sulfide minerals.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Kitadai geoelectrochemical room-temperature route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 electroreduction and methyl thioacetate synthesis on partially reduced NiS at neutral pH, then acetyl transfer to pantetheine and CoA-like acceptor.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formate-first vent route\",\n      \"description\": \"Alkaline vent reduction produces formate, then parallel vent CO production converges into methyl thioacetate formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Native iron acetate-pyruvate fixation route\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct Fe0 reduction of CO2 produces pyruvate/formate/acetate, feeding downstream thioester chemistry through pyruvate and surface or hydrothermal convergence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Preiner hydrothermal pyruvate branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Greigite/magnetite generate pyruvate from H2 and CO2, followed by transfer to the surface UV thioesterification branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Cody high-pressure organometallic pyruvate branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Deep hydrothermal FeS-carbonyl chemistry makes pyruvate, which later enters surface UV-mediated thioacetate formation and biochemical transfer.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic surface pyruvate route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN-based surface protometabolism yields pyruvate, which is photochemically converted to thioacetate ester and then to acetyl pantetheine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Pantetheine-first proto-cofactor route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface pantetheine synthesis proceeds independently and later captures acetyl groups from hydrothermal methyl thioacetate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetyl phosphate bridge route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal methyl thioacetate is converted to acetyl phosphate as an energy-rich intermediate before the acetyl group is considered available for later biochemical capture.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual-convergence vent-to-surface-to-biochemical route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO and formate production, surface pyruvate generation, and pantetheine synthesis converge on a shared thioester hub and then the speculative acetyl-CoA endpoint.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", 