to surface photochemical thioesterification and later biochemical exchange chemistry. It is a strong vent-to-surface proto-metabolic pathway, but again reaches supported acetyl-thioester analog chemistry more convincingly than full acetyl-CoA.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_013"], "suggestions": ["State more explicitly that the route validates pyruvate-centered convergence and activated acetyl transfer, not complete CoA biosynthesis.", "Provide conditions for thioester-phosphate exchange and pantetheine trapping."]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_005": 0.9, "rxn_010": 0.83, "rxn_013": 0.78, "rxn_014": 0.2}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.67, "pathway_coherence": 0.76, "environmental_progression": 0.81, "target_achievement": 0.3, "overall_confidence": 0.66, "feedback": "The Cody-style high-pressure organometallic pyruvate synthesis is literature-supported and appropriately distinct from vent H2/CO2 reduction. However, conversion from pyruvate into the exact S-methyl thioacetate node via UV disulfide chemistry is less direct, and the pathway still ends in a speculative CoA-transfer step. Good as a convergent branch to pyruvate, but not as a validated target route.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_014"], "suggestions": ["Use this pathway primarily to support pyruvate as a hub rather than as a complete route to acetyl-CoA.", "Add a better-defined methyl-thiol source and clarify whether the pyruvate product is pyruvic acid or pyruvate under pathway conditions."]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_006": 0.62, "rxn_007": 0.74, "rxn_010": 0.83, "rxn_013": 0.78, "rxn_014": 0.2}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.61, "pathway_coherence": 0.7, "environmental_progression": 0.76, "target_achievement": 0.29, "overall_confidence": 0.6, "feedback": "The cyanosulfidic branch captures the spirit of Sutherland-type protometabolism and the literature connection from pyruvate to UV thioesterification. The weakest point is