{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T12:44:52.851963", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.9\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Acetyl-CoA\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This literature-guided network treats acetyl-CoA as the formal target while explicitly grounding all experimentally supported chemistry in prebiotic acetyl-thioester formation and proto-CoA subunit generation. The network therefore converges on S-methyl thioacetate, acetyl phosphate, acetyl-pantetheine, and pantetheine as the strongest literature-supported intermediates, and includes a final explicitly speculative completion to full acetyl-CoA only to satisfy the requested target. Ten distinct pathways are encoded by recombining five experimentally grounded entry routes: W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user iron-sulfur carbonylation, Russell-Martin alkaline vent C1 reduction, native-metal CO2 fixation, Cody high-pressure organometallic pyruvate synthesis, and Sutherland-Leqraa cyanosulfidic/UV pyruvate-to-thioester chemistry, together with Fairchild-Powner pantetheine synthesis and acetyl-group transfer chemistry. Environmental interconnection is implemented as Hydrothermal generation of CO, formate, acetate, methanethiol and pyruvate; Surface generation of pyruvate and UV-driven thioester precursors; and Biochemical transfer/exchange to pantetheine-derived proto-cofactors and the speculative CoA endpoint.\n\nMOLECULES (15 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: CO (carbon monoxide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: CH2O2 (formate/formic acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_005: C2H4O2 (acetate/acetic acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: CH4S (methyl mercaptan) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: C3H4O3 (pyruvic acid/pyruvate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: CH3S2CH3 (dimethyl disulfide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C3H3NO (pyruvonitrile) [intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C3H6O3S (methyl thioacetate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C2H5O5P (acetyl phosphate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C11H22N2O4S (pantetheine) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C13H24N2O5S2 (acetyl-pantetheine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C23H38N7O17P3S (acetyl-coenzyme A) [target]\n  - mol_015: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [starting]\n\nREACTIONS (13 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_004 (Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate on greigite/awaruite-like surfaces) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_003 (Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to CO on Ni-Fe sulfide surfaces) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_001 -> mol_005, mol_007, mol_004 (Native metal CO2 fixation to acetate and pyruvate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_004: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_007 (Hydrothermal H2/CO2 fixation to pyruvate on greigite/magnetite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_005: mol_003, mol_006 -> mol_007 (High-pressure organometallic pyruvate synthesis from CO and thiols) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_006: mol_003, mol_006 -> mol_010 (Iron-sulfur world carbonylation of methanethiol to S-methyl thioacetate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_007: mol_001, mol_006 -> mol_003, mol_010 (Geoelectrochemical room-temperature thioester synthesis on partially reduced sulfides) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_008: mol_015 -> mol_009, mol_007 (Cyanosulfidic UV route to pyruvate precursor pool) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_007, mol_008 -> mol_010 (UV pyruvate-to-thioacetate ester formation via disulfide chemistry) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_010 -> mol_011 (Thioester-phosphate exchange to acetyl phosphate) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_011: mol_015 -> mol_012 (Prebiotic pantetheine synthesis) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_012: mol_010, mol_012 -> mol_013 (Acetyl transfer from methyl thioacetate to pantetheine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_013: mol_013 -> mol_014 (Speculative completion from acetyl-pantetheine to acetyl-CoA) [Biochemical]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user direct carbonylation route (4 steps)\n  - P2: Geoelectrochemical vent route (3 steps)\n  - P3: Preiner hydrothermal pyruvate to surface thioester route (4 steps)\n  - P4: Native iron pyruvate branch (4 steps)\n  - P5: Cody high-pressure organometallic branch (5 steps)\n  - P6: Cyanosulfidic surface-only thioester entry (4 steps)\n  - P7: Formate-supported hydrothermal convergence route (5 steps)\n  - P8: Acetyl phosphate protoenergetic route (4 steps)\n  - P9: Pantetheine-first convergence route (4 steps)\n  - P10: Dual-hub integrated vent-to-pool route (6 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_003, mol_007, mol_010, mol_012, mol_004\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of acetyl-CoA: from minerals to metabolism\n\n**Acetyl-CoA \u2014 or more precisely its simpler thioester analogs like methyl thioacetate \u2014 can be synthesized under plausible prebiotic conditions through at least five demonstrated routes**, all converging on transition-metal-sulfide-catalyzed carbonylation chemistry that mirrors the most ancient carbon fixation pathway in biology. The central reaction, CO + CH\u2083SH \u2192 CH\u2083COSCH\u2083 on nickel-iron sulfide surfaces, was first demonstrated by Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user in 1997 at just 0.2\u20130.5% yield, but has since been pushed to **35\u201356% yield** at room temperature and neutral pH through geoelectrochemical approaches (Kitadai et al., 2021, *Communications Chemistry*). Meanwhile, the 2024 breakthrough prebiotic synthesis of pantetheine \u2014 CoA's functional subunit \u2014 by Fairchild, Islam, Singh, and Powner (*Science*, 2024) has dramatically narrowed the gap between simple thioesters and the full cofactor. These advances place acetyl thioester chemistry at the nexus of the origin-of-life problem, connecting geochemistry to the emergence of core metabolism.\n\n---\n\n## Five convergent routes to prebiotic acetyl thioesters\n\nMultiple independent research programs have proposed or demonstrated pathways to acetyl thioesters from simple molecules (CO\u2082, CO, H\u2082, H\u2082S, CH\u2083SH). Each route emerges from a distinct geochemical scenario, yet all converge on remarkably similar chemistry \u2014 the metal-catalyzed union of a one-carbon carbonyl unit with a thiol.\n\n**Route 1: Iron-sulfur world carbonylation (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user).** G\u00fcnter W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user proposed in 1988 (*Microbiological Reviews*) that life originated on iron sulfide mineral surfaces through autotrophic surface metabolism. The thermodynamic engine is the \"pyrite-pulled\" reaction: FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + H\u2082 (\u0394G\u00b0 = **\u221238 to \u221242 kJ/mol**), which provides reducing equivalents for CO\u2082 fixation. In this framework, CO\u2082 is reduced to CO on mineral surfaces, then CO undergoes carbonylation with methanethiol to form methyl thioacetate \u2014 a prebiotic analog of acetyl-CoA. The mechanism involves nickel-mediated organometallic intermediates (Ni-CO, Ni-CH\u2083, Ni-acetyl) that parallel both the biological acetyl-CoA synthase reaction and the industrial Monsanto acetic acid process.\n\n**Route 2: Alkaline hydrothermal vent synthesis (Russell and Martin).** Michael Russell proposed in 1994 (*Journal of Molecular Evolution*) that life emerged at submarine alkaline hydrothermal vents, where serpentinization-derived H\u2082-rich, alkaline fluids (pH 9\u201311) encountered the CO\u2082-rich, mildly acidic Hadean ocean (pH ~5\u20136). Iron-nickel sulfide precipitates lining vent micropores catalyze a geochemical analog of the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway: CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 CO on one branch, CO\u2082 \u2192 CH\u2083-group on another, with convergence at NiFe-sulfide surfaces to form acetyl thioesters. Natural **pH gradients of ~3\u20135 units** across inorganic membranes provide an electrochemical driving force of ~250\u2013300 mV, sufficient to power CO\u2082 reduction. Martin and Russell (2007, *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B*) detailed how acetyl phosphate (\u0394G'\u2070 of hydrolysis = **\u221243 kJ/mol**, exceeding ATP's \u221231 kJ/mol) would serve as the primordial energy currency.\n\n**Route 3: Native metal CO\u2082 reduction (Moran, Varma, Muchowska).** Varma, Muchowska, Chatelain, and Moran (2018, *Nature Ecology & Evolution*) showed that native iron (Fe\u2070) directly reduces CO\u2082 to acetate (**up to 280 \u00b5M**), pyruvate, and formate at 30\u2013100\u00b0C under 1\u201340 bar CO\u2082. This bypasses the kinetic barriers that stymied earlier attempts at H\u2082-driven CO\u2082 reduction. The midpoint potential of Fe\u2070 oxidation is sufficient to reduce CO\u2082 without the flavin-based electron bifurcation that biological systems require. Preiner et al. (2020, *Nature Ecology & Evolution*) extended this using hydrothermal minerals \u2014 **greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084), and awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe)** \u2014 to produce formate (up to **200 mM**), acetate (~100 \u00b5M), and pyruvate (~10 \u00b5M) from H\u2082 + CO\u2082 at 100\u00b0C. Beyazay et al. (2023, *Nature Communications*) achieved the same product spectrum at just **25\u00b0C** under 25 bar with Ni\u2083Fe nanoparticles, and demonstrated further conversion of pyruvate to citramalate.\n\n**Route 4: Cyanosulfidic protometabolism (Sutherland).** John Sutherland's group at MRC Cambridge developed a systems chemistry approach where HCN and H\u2082S, driven by UV photoredox cycling with Cu(I)/Cu(II) catalysis, generate precursors to nucleotides, amino acids, and lipids from common feedstocks (Patel et al., 2015, *Nature Chemistry*). While this framework does not directly produce acetyl thioesters, it generates **pyruvate in ~14% yield** through UV-driven oxidation of \u03b1-hydroxy acids (Ritson, 2021, *Science Advances*) \u2014 a key branch-point intermediate for thioester formation via oxidative decarboxylation. Critically, Leqraa et al. (2020, *Scientific Reports*) demonstrated that pyruvate reacts with disulfides under UV irradiation to yield thioacetate esters without requiring an external oxidant, bridging cyanosulfidic chemistry to thioester metabolism.\n\n**Route 5: High-pressure organometallic synthesis (Cody).** Cody et al. (2000, *Science*) demonstrated that at 250\u00b0C and 50\u2013200 MPa \u2014 conditions simulating deep hydrothermal systems \u2014 CO reacts with iron sulfide and alkyl thiols to form organometallic iron-sulfur-carbonyl phases that produce pyruvic acid. This pressure-enhanced pathway operates through organometallic intermediates structurally analogous to CODH/ACS active sites.\n\n---\n\n## Key intermediates and branch points\n\nThe path from CO\u2082 to acetyl thioesters passes through a small number of critical intermediates, several of which serve as branch points connecting multiple biosynthetic pathways.\n\n**Carbon monoxide** is the pivotal C\u2081 intermediate in virtually all routes. It is generated from CO\u2082 by electroreduction on iron sulfide minerals, by the reverse water-gas shift reaction (CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO + H\u2082O) on Fe/Ni surfaces, or by UV photolysis. CO binds to nickel centers on mineral surfaces \u2014 the same chemistry exploited by the CODH enzyme's C-cluster \u2014 and undergoes migratory insertion with methyl groups to form the C\u2013C bond of the acetyl unit. **Formate (HCOO\u207b)** is the first stable reduction product of CO\u2082, produced in extraordinary abundance \u2014 up to **200 mM** on awaruite (Preiner et al., 2020). Formate is the entry point of the methyl branch of the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway and can be further reduced to formaldehyde, methanol, and methyl groups.\n\n**Methanethiol (CH\u2083SH)** is the essential thiol substrate. It is present in modern hydrothermal fluids at micromolar to low-millimolar concentrations and can be generated abiotically from CO\u2082 reduction in sulfide-rich environments. Methanethiol provides both the thiol leaving group and, in some formulations, the methyl group for the carbonylation reaction. **Pyruvate** occupies a unique position as the most connected branch-point metabolite \u2014 it is the precursor to all amino acids (via transamination), to acetyl-CoA (via oxidative decarboxylation), and to oxaloacetate (via carboxylation). Goldford et al. (2017, *Cell*) computationally identified pyruvate and glyoxylate as the most well-connected C-H-O compounds in a hypothetical phosphate-free proto-metabolism. Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (2019, *Nature*) demonstrated that Fe\u00b2\u207a promotes a reaction network starting from pyruvate and glyoxylate that builds **9 of 11 Krebs cycle intermediates**.\n\n**S-Methyl thioacetate (CH\u2083COSCH\u2083)** is the simplest activated thioester analog of acetyl-CoA. Its hydrolysis releases **\u221231 kJ/mol** of free energy \u2014 comparable to ATP hydrolysis \u2014 making it a plausible primordial energy currency as proposed by de Duve's \"thioester world\" hypothesis (1991). **Acetyl phosphate** bridges thioester and phosphate metabolism: formed non-enzymatically from acetyl thioesters and inorganic phosphate, it has an even higher phosphorylating potential (\u0394G'\u2070 = \u221243 kJ/mol) than ATP.\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts mirror enzyme active sites with striking fidelity\n\nThe most compelling evidence connecting prebiotic geochemistry to biochemistry is the structural and functional correspondence between hydrothermal mineral catalysts and the metalloenzyme active sites that catalyze acetyl-CoA synthesis in modern organisms.\n\n**Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**, the sulfide analog of magnetite, contains cubic **[Fe\u2084S\u2084] structural units** that are geometrically identical to the [4Fe-4S] thiocubane clusters found in ferredoxins and in the CODH/ACS enzyme complex. Fe\u2013S bond distances in greigite match those in ferredoxin active sites within **0.01\u20130.13 \u00c5** (Roldan et al., 2015, *Chemical Communications*). Greigite was confirmed to be thermodynamically stable \u2014 not metastable as previously assumed \u2014 with low surface energy supporting nanoparticle catalytic activity (Navarro-Gonz\u00e1lez et al., 2020, *PNAS*). Electrochemically, greigite reduces CO\u2082 under ambient conditions to formic acid, methanol, acetic acid, and pyruvic acid (Roldan et al., 2015). **Nickel-bearing greigite** structurally resembles the C-cluster ([NiFe\u2083S\u2084]) of carbon monoxide dehydrogenase (CODH), which catalyzes the reversible reduction CO\u2082 \u21cc CO with virtually no overpotential. Doping FeS with Ni to form violarite (FeNi\u2082S\u2084) enhances CO\u2082 electroreduction selectivity **~85-fold** compared to pure FeS.\n\n**Mackinawite (FeS)**, the initial precipitate from Fe\u00b2\u207a + S\u00b2\u207b in hydrothermal systems, has a layered tetragonal structure comprising [2Fe-2S] rhombic units \u2014 the same motif as [2Fe-2S] ferredoxin clusters. It forms spontaneous inorganic membranes at alkaline hydrothermal vents. When partially electroreduced to metallic Fe\u2070 (designated FeS_PERM), mackinawite shows exceptional catalytic capability for multiple reactions in the reverse tricarboxylic acid cycle (Kitadai et al., 2019). Nan et al. (2024, *Nature Communications*) showed mackinawite catalyzes H\u2082-driven CO\u2082 reduction to methanol at 80\u2013120\u00b0C, with **Mn-doped FeS increasing methanol production five-fold**.\n\n**Awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe)**, a native nickel-iron alloy formed during serpentinization, proved the most efficient catalyst for multi-carbon product formation from H\u2082 + CO\u2082 in Preiner et al.'s 2020 experiments. Its catalytic role parallels the Ni\u2070 site in the ACS A-cluster, where nickel cycles between oxidation states to mediate methyl migration and CO insertion. **Green rust/fougerite**, a mixed-valence Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b3\u207a layered double hydroxide, has been proposed by Russell (2023, *Frontiers in Microbiology*) as a membrane-spanning catalytic engine at alkaline vents. Its ~150 hydrous interlayers can concentrate anions up to **10\u2076-fold**, potentially solving the concentration problem, while its redox versatility (stable across Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe_total ratios of 1/3 to 2/3) enables electron bifurcation analogous to biological systems.\n\nThe biological acetyl-CoA synthase (ACS) A-cluster contains a unique [Ni_p\u2013Ni_d\u2013Fe\u2084S\u2084] center where the proximal nickel (Ni_p) cycles between Ni\u2070/Ni\u00b9\u207a/Ni\u00b2\u207a states during catalysis \u2014 binding CO, accepting a methyl group, forming an acetyl intermediate, and transferring it to CoA-SH via reductive thiolysis. Manesis et al. (2022, *PNAS*) created an artificial nickel metalloenzyme within the azurin protein scaffold that reproduces this chemistry at **up to 70% yield**, demonstrating that the catalytic principle requires only a single nickel center in a minimal protein environment. Wilson et al. (2024, *JACS*) synthesized heterometallic [NiFe\u2084S\u2084] clusters by inserting Ni\u2070 into oxidized [Fe\u2084S\u2084]\u00b3\u207a, establishing the first experimental precedent for the Ni\u00b9\u207a oxidation state in iron-sulfur cluster chemistry \u2014 a critical mechanistic link between mineral and enzymatic catalysis. Jordan et al. (2021, *Nature Communications*) demonstrated that [4Fe-4S] and [2Fe-2S] clusters **self-assemble spontaneously** from Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b3\u207a, S\u00b2\u207b, and micromolar cysteine at alkaline pH, with bicarbonate stabilizing the clusters. These clusters exhibit midpoint redox potentials of approximately **\u2212500 mV vs SHE**, appropriate for CO\u2082 reduction.\n\n---\n\n## Landmark experiments and quantitative benchmarks\n\nThe experimental evidence for prebiotic thioester synthesis has progressed dramatically from early proof-of-concept demonstrations to increasingly realistic and efficient systems.\n\n**Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997, *Science* 276: 245\u2013247)** provided the foundational demonstration: coprecipitated NiS/FeS in sealed anaerobic vials at 100\u00b0C under 1.05 bar CO, with 100 \u00b5mol CH\u2083SH in 10 mL aqueous solution at initial pH ~8, produced **41 \u00b5mol acetic acid** and detectable methyl thioacetate after 7 days. With NiS alone (no FeS), 7\u20139 \u00b5mol of methyl thioacetate formed in 20 hours. Adding catalytic selenium enabled one-pot synthesis from CO and H\u2082S alone, without externally added methanethiol. However, the CO concentration (~350 mM in solution) was **~500\u00d7 higher** and CH\u2083SH (~3,700\u00d7) higher than concentrations measured in natural hydrothermal fluids (Camprub\u00ed et al., 2017, *IUBMB Life*), limiting geochemical plausibility.\n\n**Kitadai et al. (2021, *Communications Chemistry* 4: 37)** achieved a transformative advance: under simulated geoelectrochemical conditions (\u22120.6 to \u22121.0 V vs SHE), NiS gradually reduced to Ni\u2083S\u2082 and then Ni\u2070, accumulating surface-bound CO from CO\u2082 electroreduction. This partially reduced NiS (NiS_PERM) catalyzed methyl thioacetate formation at **room temperature, neutral pH, with up to 35% yield** based on CO. Coprecipitation with CoS pushed yields to **56%**. This represents a **~175-fold improvement** over Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's original yield, under far milder conditions. The geoelectrochemical driving force \u2014 redox gradients across hydrothermal chimney walls \u2014 is geologically realistic.\n\n**Preiner et al. (2020, *Nature Ecology & Evolution* 4: 534\u2013542)** demonstrated that three naturally occurring hydrothermal minerals catalyze a geochemical analog of the complete Wood-Ljungdahl pathway: greigite, magnetite, and awaruite convert H\u2082 + CO\u2082 at 100\u00b0C in alkaline solution to formate (**up to 200 mM**), acetate (~100 \u00b5M), pyruvate (~10 \u00b5M), methanol (~100 \u00b5M), and methane. The product spectrum precisely mirrors the biological pathway's intermediates and products.\n\n**Cody et al. (2000, *Science* 289: 1337\u20131340)** demonstrated pyruvate synthesis at 250\u00b0C and 50\u2013200 MPa from CO + FeS + alkyl thiols, showing that high-pressure hydrothermal conditions favor organometallic iron-sulfur-carbonyl intermediates. **Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (2019, *Nature* 569: 104\u2013107)** showed Fe\u00b2\u207a promotes construction of 9 of 11 Krebs cycle intermediates from pyruvate and glyoxylate, with addition of hydroxylamine and Fe\u2070 yielding four biological amino acids \u2014 demonstrating that prebiotic thioester-related chemistry connects seamlessly to amino acid biosynthesis.\n\nRecent work has expanded both the reaction scope and environmental settings. **El Qami et al. (2025, *Scientific Reports*)** showed 1,4-diacids form cyclic anhydrides upon drying over silica, which react with thiols to produce succinyl and citryl thioester analogs \u2014 a self-activating mechanism requiring no ATP equivalent. **Frenkel-Pinter et al. (2022, *Nature Communications*)** demonstrated that simply drying mercaptoacids with amino acids produces thiodepsipeptides containing both peptide and thioester bonds across a wide range of pH and temperature. **Cho et al. (2025, *Nature Chemistry*)** showed that cysteine reacting spontaneously with short-chain thioesters produces protocell-like structures, while **Kent et al. (2025, *ACS Central Science*)** demonstrated that tRNAs acylated with thioesters support efficient protein biosynthesis by wild-type ribosomes \u2014 evidence that thioester intermediates may have preceded oxoester intermediates in early translation.\n\n---\n\n## Environments that favor each step of the pathway\n\nDifferent geochemical settings optimize different steps of the pathway from CO\u2082 to acetyl thioesters, suggesting either a single environment with diverse microenvironments or a multi-setting scenario.\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents** (Lost City-type: 40\u2013120\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311, H\u2082 up to 14 mM, continuous for >100,000 years) are optimal for the initial CO\u2082 reduction steps. Serpentinization generates both the reductant (H\u2082) and the catalyst (awaruite, magnetite, greigite) simultaneously. The pH gradient across FeS/NiS membranes (~5 units on Hadean Earth) provides an electrochemical driving force of 250\u2013300 mV \u2014 sufficient to power CO\u2082 reduction to CO and formate. Microporous inorganic compartments within chimney structures solve the concentration problem while providing proto-cellular confinement (Russell and Hall, 1997). However, thioester stability is severely limited under these conditions: **methyl thioacetate half-life at pH 10, 100\u00b0C is only ~43 seconds** (Mayer et al., 2024, *iScience*), compared to **155 days at pH 7, 23\u00b0C** (Brosnan et al., 2011, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*). This stability constraint strongly favors thioester accumulation in **cooler, more acidic microenvironments** \u2014 perhaps at the ocean-facing exterior of vent structures where mixing with acidic seawater moderates both temperature and pH.\n\n**Surface evaporitic pools** and terrestrial hot springs favor condensation and polymerization steps. Wet-dry cycling drives anhydride and thioester bond formation during drying phases. UV irradiation provides photochemical energy for radical reactions, including pyruvate oxidative decarboxylation to acetyl thioesters (Leqraa et al., 2020). Nan et al. (2024, *Nature Communications*) demonstrated FeS-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to methanol at 80\u2013120\u00b0C in conditions mimicking terrestrial hot springs, with UV-visible light enhancing activity. **Thermophoresis** in rock pore networks can selectively accumulate diverse prebiotic building blocks through temperature gradients (Matreux et al., 2024).\n\n---\n\n## Unresolved challenges and the path forward\n\nDespite remarkable experimental progress, several fundamental problems remain.\n\n**The CoA complexity gap** is perhaps the most significant. Acetyl-CoA is a large, information-rich molecule containing pantothenic acid, \u03b2-alanine, cysteamine, and 3'-phospho-ADP \u2014 each component presenting its own prebiotic synthesis challenge. However, three developments have substantially narrowed this gap. First, **Fairchild et al. (2024, *Science* 383: 911\u2013918)** achieved the first prebiotically plausible synthesis of pantetheine \u2014 CoA's catalytically active subunit \u2014 through chemoselective nitrile chemistry in water at room temperature, dramatically outperforming Miller's earlier attempt (Keefe, Newton, and Miller, 1995, *Nature*). Second, Goldford et al. (2017, *Cell*) computationally demonstrated that substituting pantetheine for CoA maintains network viability in a phosphate-free proto-metabolism. Third, even simpler thiols \u2014 methanethiol, cysteamine, coenzyme M (HSCH\u2082CH\u2082SO\u2083\u207b) \u2014 can serve the same chemical function, as demonstrated by near-quantitative aminoacyl-thiol yields using coenzyme M (Singh et al., 2025, *Nature*).\n\n**The concentration problem** persists for dilute products in open aqueous environments. Proposed solutions include microporous vent confinement, thermophoretic accumulation in rock fissures, wet-dry cycling in surface pools, eutectic concentration in ice, and the remarkable **10\u2076-fold concentration** achievable in green rust interlayers. Thiol-thioester exchange (k = 1.7 M\u207b\u00b9s\u207b\u00b9 at pH 7, 23\u00b0C) is several orders of magnitude faster than thioester hydrolysis, meaning that even dilute thioester pools can efficiently transfer their acetyl groups to new thiol acceptors before being lost to hydrolysis.\n\n**Selectivity and the \"chemical mess\" problem** \u2014 the tendency of prebiotic reactions to produce complex mixtures of products rather than the specific molecules biology uses \u2014 remains a core challenge. Mineral surfaces provide some selectivity through preferential adsorption and oriented catalysis, but lack the precise substrate positioning of enzyme active sites. The emerging \"systems chemistry\" approach (Sutherland, Powner) addresses this by identifying reaction networks where selectivity emerges from the interplay of multiple concurrent reactions rather than from any single selective step.\n\n**The mineral-to-enzyme transition** \u2014 how catalysis migrated from mineral surfaces to soluble iron-sulfur clusters to metalloproteins \u2014 is incompletely understood. Jordan et al.'s demonstration of spontaneous [4Fe-4S] cluster self-assembly from simple precursors and Wilson et al.'s synthesis of heterometallic [NiFe\u2084S\u2084] clusters provide critical missing pieces, but the full trajectory from greigite surfaces to CODH/ACS holoenzyme remains speculative. Notably, the redox bifunctionality of nickel (cycling between Ni\u2070/Ni\u00b9\u207a/Ni\u00b2\u207a/Ni\u00b3\u207a) that is essential for ACS catalysis has not been observed in natural nickel-bearing minerals \u2014 only under imposed electrochemical conditions \u2014 raising questions about whether mineral catalysis alone could have supported the full carbonylation mechanism.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of acetyl thioesters has progressed from theoretical proposals to experimentally demonstrated chemistry achieving yields comparable to enzymatic reactions. The field has converged on a core insight: **the same nickel-iron-sulfide chemistry that catalyzes acetyl-CoA synthesis in the most ancient biological pathway also operates on mineral surfaces under geologically realistic conditions**. The structural identity between greigite [Fe\u2084S\u2084] units and ferredoxin clusters, and between Ni-doped iron sulfides and CODH/ACS active sites, is not merely analogical but reflects a direct evolutionary continuity from geochemistry to biochemistry. The most productive current direction combines the Strasbourg group's native-metal CO\u2082 reduction chemistry with the Kitadai group's geoelectrochemical thioester synthesis and the Powner group's prebiotic CoA-precursor synthesis \u2014 together these define a plausible, experimentally grounded pathway from volcanic gases to the central energy-coupling molecule of all life. The critical next milestone is demonstrating a complete, continuous sequence from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 to an acetyl thioester in a single geochemically realistic reactor \u2014 a goal that, given the pace of recent advances, appears increasingly within reach.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"feedback\": \"<pathway-specific feedback>\",\n            \"approved\": <true if confidence >= 0.8>,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_ids with issues\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"improvements\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"<id of best pathway>\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"<overall assessment>\",\n    \"hub_quality\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"convergence_quality\": <0.0-1.0>\n}\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.97,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.12\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibili