wnstream thioester chemistry is more defensible.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_008\",\n        \"rxn_013\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Expand the cyanosulfidic sequence into a multistep precursor network rather than one compressed reaction\",\n        \"Include sulfide and UV-active metal mediation explicitly\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.96,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.12\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.74,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.9,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.38,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.74,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is a well-connected hydrothermal convergence pathway using formate and CO as realistic vent intermediates before thioester capture. It aligns well with Russell-Martin and Kitadai-style chemistry. As elsewhere, the pathway is convincing to acetyl thioesters and acetyl-pantetheine, but not to full acetyl-CoA.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_013\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Leverage formate more explicitly as a branch toward methyl equivalents rather than leaving it mainly topological\",\n        \"Treat acetyl-pantetheine as the experimentally grounded terminus\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.97,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.12\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.69,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.8,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.38,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.68,\n      \"feedback\": \"The protoenergetic logic is sound: acetyl thioesters can plausibly exchange with phosphate to form acety